The Prague Stock Exchange fell into the negative at the end of trading
After the morning sharp drop, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares amounted to almost half of the normal daily trade.
Right from the beginning of Tuesday's trading, the Prague Stock Exchange continued its Monday drop, falling by almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
Even in our country, the market reaction to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the plan to stabilize the local financial sector, is reflected.
Stock Crash in Asia
Stocks on stock exchanges in Asia experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices eventually erased some of their losses during the day.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange's Hang Seng index lost nearly four percent in trading, but later erased some of its losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell 3.8 percent, while markets were closed in Shanghai.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually reduced losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent, according to the country's index.
"The timing of the U.S. bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world," said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong's monetary office.
Hong Kong, although part of China, sets monetary policy on its own, i.e. without dependence on the Chinese central bank.
Hong Kong has interest rates on par with the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should quickly return to negotiations and approve the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, he said, there is a risk that other countries will feel the impact.
US Stock Bloodbath
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, on which up to $ 700 billion (almost CZK 12 trillion) was supposed to be spent.
Lawmakers ignored President George W. Bush's call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday, with major stock indexes posting their biggest fall in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones fell by almost seven percent and last recorded a drop of similar magnitude in 1987.
The index was already falling before the vote, but as soon as it became clear that the bill did not pass in the House, the index went into free fall.
Congress backtracks: U.S. government can pump $700 billion into banks
Top officials in the US Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of a financial assistance agreement for the US financial system.
It will be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks to approve a rescue plan in the form of $700 billion (approximately 12 trillion crowns) in financial assistance for the U.S. financial system.
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must finalize some details of the agreement before they can release the final version of the bill and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be debated on the floor of the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
The Senate could vote on the plan probably not until Wednesday at the earliest, according to sources.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first major psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
But then there will be a "disillusionment" due to the complexity of the mechanisms by which to help markets achieve it in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences of opinion on what the market stabilization package should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
She said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to finalise the government fund.
It should buy unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which drag financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we're there," Paulson said.
Signal for Asian trading
The global financial crisis has had a significant impact on stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors from trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone where a congressional decision could affect Monday's trading.
But it is not yet clear when both houses of the US Congress will vote on the bill, or whether last-minute negotiations might stall on an issue.
Lawmakers hope it will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law will undergo a number of changes.
The total amount allocated to assistance to the scheme is to be divided into two parts.
An initial $350 billion is to be available as soon as possible, as requested by President George W. Bush.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not doing its job, in a succession of another $100 billion and later a final $350 billion.
Bush praised progress in negotiations
The president can veto the decision, but Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, the program's basic idea, which was to raise funds to buy back bad mortgage securities that have plummeted in value because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, remained.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President Bush is also satisfied with the progress of the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and appreciated "a bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitations of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the chief negotiator, said lawmakers agreed on accountability for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing relief, timing funding the plan.
The new law also aims to restrict so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee to supervise the fund.
This should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We've worked very this and we've made great progress toward a deal that works and is useful to the market and to all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also counts on assistance for homeowners who have repayment problems.
The government should negotiate new payments on the mortgages it buys in order to reduce the monthly cost of repayments for borrowers and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to David Marek, chief economist of Patria Finance, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"This is because it is not known by what mechanism and at what price the troubled assets will be purchased.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government will divide the losses between them," Marek told news server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be approved now or early next week is not so important, according to Mark.
"It is much more important that the congressmen agree this week that they support this plan and that they will approve it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement to approve it is the most important at the moment," Marek emphasized.
The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, together they have 29 percent
According to the first preliminary results, Sunday's early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a significant weakening of both parties of the grand coalition and a significant strengthening of right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly heavy losses, with the position of current chairman Wilhelm Molterer seriously shaking.
On the other hand, the election leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian governor Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the Social Democrats (SPÖ) remain the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but have lost 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last election in 2006.
Even worse was the ÖVP, which lost almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both of these big parties in Austria's post-war history, and especially for the People's Party, which triggered the early elections, a disastrous result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ in preferences.
But voters apparently punished them for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there was speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman and current Vice Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party bureau.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the still most likely outcome of the election outcome, the renewal of the SPÖ-ÖVP grand coalition.
However, due to the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) provisionally won 18 percent and the BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - the Social Democrats also expressed fears of a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) on a joint government, which even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already declared that he is ready to cooperate with any party and expects to return to national politics in Vienna, is apparently betting on this development.
The Green Party also entered parliament, but lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
Apparently, none of the other parties crossed the four percent threshold and did not get into parliament.
Battle on a knife's edge: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
From this it seems clear that it is better to buy just a phone.
Still, there are enough reasons to get a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the demands of the future owner.
It's hard to get a top-notch expensive turntable to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc album.
On the one hand, such musical products are not released on LPs and, from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this.
However, if your shelves are crammed with vinyl with art rock, jazz or blues, you probably dream of such a turntable.
It's the same with music on the go, i.e. compressed music, simply - music in MP3.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For someone it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan will hardly try headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some top music players can do much more than just play music, but what most mobiles do not even happen to.
No current device is as versatile as a phone.
In addition to primary functions, phone calls and texting, it can play music and video, record both, has a better camera, a worse camera and can even navigate.
And when you think about smartphones and communicators, you'll even have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle, because no fridge can grill and no TV can photograph anything.
The versatility of the mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, usually it is much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap mobiles, therefore, count on the fact that they will not play for more than a few hours.
If you still call every now and then, get one more charger for work - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you will not have this problem, even the worse ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music on mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and not every one of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to a memory card, but only a few card readers can handle miniature memory cards that are used in mobile phones without reduction.
With some exceptions (iPod), you do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players already create a music library sorted by artist name, album title, genre or user rating.
Some devices display only a tree structure of directories similar to Explorer in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Players are easier to operate, mobile phones are more capable
When choosing a particular device, be particularly interested in the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, of course, the comfort of control.
If music is primarily a backdrop for you and you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram, all you need is any mobile phone that plays MP3.
Which can really almost any mobile.
You don't even have to keep track of what music formats your mobile phone or player can do.
MP3s can handle everyone, and the vast majority of music that reaches you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widespread and the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobiles also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit the relevant website of the operator (or other provider) via the mobile Internet and buy the song or album.
This service alone could be a compelling argument for buying a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is lousy and is mostly limited to quick-fermented radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry a mobile phone with them all the time.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you can feel your phone in your pocket while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least wired hands-free.
If not, you can use the integrated speaker that almost every mobile has, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of music mobiles for many will be the price.
The cheapest ones are usually under three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns you will get a very decent walkman.
Mostly, however, you will be limited by the absence of an output to conventional headphones.
The best and technically most equipped phones with a 3.5 mm jack for common headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can be controlled by everyone.
The minimum of functions, similarity of control with a previously common cassette recorder or gramophone is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of accidentally turned on mobile internet and subsequently a giant bill for data transfer.
What device to reach for
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the appropriate card, you will fit into two thousand crowns.
But beware.
On base models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can handle 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriveru.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are a more demanding listener, reach for specialized mobiles - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of operation is close to a separate MP3 player.
The furthest in the field is Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles from the Walkman series have the same user interface as separately sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours), will take you MP3 players from the above-mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would force the classic ones to become cheaper.
Maybe he will not be missing for long.
We have written about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe many times on Mobil.cz.
This was confirmed by the CTO, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of roaming fee regulation, a paradoxical situation may arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to go into battle.
It may sound paradoxical, after all, we have three mobile networks and penetration well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (CTO), who has said several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic, often echoes in this.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network probably does not have much chance (after all, it would be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is one more option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, to which even conventional operators had to respond.
At the same time, even before the entry of pikes such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, similar voices were heard in the UK as in our country.
But it turned out that there is a place for such operators and they can be really successful.
After all, we don't have to look too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator.
Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns, among other things, U:fona in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a fresh target group can also be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"The right guys are voting for Mobilking — an operator they like and trust," says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual carrier.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could catch on in our country.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesman for Vodafone, doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region," Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor arises.
The GTS Novera Group has long been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator, and would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor to Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this option with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to advance negotiations with some of them," says Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesperson.
So maybe better times are ahead.
From unofficial information, it seems that we should see the first virtual operator perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its emergence is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room for a full-fledged virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," said Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónica O2's Press Department in a statement to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also referred to by other operators.
Martina Kemrova, spokesperson for T-Mobile, adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "So far, we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which it would be possible to build further."
He adds: "It will be difficult for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would need to have a concrete agreement on the table to think in this short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - one hand with operators
The actions of mobile operators are easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, lead to a drop in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to get onboard?
The fact that operators are interested in something, they can pull together is also evidenced by the scramble around the creation of U:fon.
Perhaps the greatest pressure towards the CTO came at the time of the creation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTU website.
But now U:fon is useful as an argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrova commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been enhanced by the entry of a fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player would place high demands on it and, above all, on its services."
Given this approach of mobile operators, however, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is striking.
This is not just about the position of the CTO, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - does not have the powers to interfere in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after a contract has been concluded between the mobile operator and the virtual operator on the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential bidders was probably not interesting enough for classic operators," said Kristián Chalupa from the External Relations Department of the Office for the Protection of Competition.
This statement will not come as a surprise from the operators' representatives.
This is more than a matter of concern from an authority that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their market position.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in prices for mobile telephone services."
Apparently, however, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the drop in prices are not among the interests of the Office.
What is truly shocking about the whole case is the touching harmony of the three mobile operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is self-explanatory.
Just as the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations is certainly just a matter of chance and fierce competition.
"The Office has not found signs of anti-competitive conduct in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have correspondingly increased responsibility for its conduct on the market.
The telecommunications regulator probably also lacks the necessary tools to open the mobile market for virtual operators," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by the CTO, according to which telecommunications are a single market from the point of view of competition.
Of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
However, even if we do not allow this argumentation, it should be at least a warning for the Office for the Protection of Competition that three mobile operators are proceeding strikingly similarly.
However, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in dealing with all operators.
Shifting responsibility to the CTO is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, by which the Office for the Protection of Competition keeps its hands off the whole matter.
We have already encountered him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the CTU's powers to the area of competition in telecommunications was not pushed through, although many experts expected it to improve the situation.
The representatives of the Office for the Protection of Competition must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's possible when no one is looking
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
Usually, these are companies engaged in multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts to the operator as a classic business customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, he will receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale resale.
"If there were cases you are talking about, it could be a breach of contractual terms that we would deal with and could result in termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrova replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that similar activity would not reach the responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is opposed to such a procedure.
They make considerable profits from the activities of these companies and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as regular customers of mobile operators."
But that should be at least strange for the CTO.
In addition, another question opens up for the Office for the Protection of Competition.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to this, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the Office for the Protection of Competition has relatively strong powers to detect such activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the operators' explanation that they have no idea about anything like this and their business conditions prohibit it.
When we will not be the most expensive
As has been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where virtual operators were established, conventional operators tried to more or less prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that regulators intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they then achieved that the first virtual operator was created and others piled on top of it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are tossing the whole case around like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that the lack of clarity in competences is more than useful in these cases.
But let's not throw a flint into the rye.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will appear in our country really soon, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If one of the operators has admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the Office for the Protection of Competition will hardly be able to remain indifferent to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Day of Czech Statehood, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek ceremonially introduced new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the leadership of Jiří Bělohlávek.
Four versions are available - with male or female solo singing, choral rendition and instrumental version.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka sang the vocals.
The authors of the arrangements of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on iHNed.cz.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful anthems.
He has previously told Czech Radio that he deliberately chose singers with young, representative voices that are distinctive and popular to sing solo variants.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both of them, and then also with the choir, that they had clear diction, that the text was well understood, that they resonated," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj (Where Is My Home) was first heard in 1834 on the boards of the Estates Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously embraced it.
The first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem after the establishment of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
