Sudetenland wanted a referendum from the US
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans asked for the Šumava to be incorporated into the United States.
This follows from a letter that is deposited in the collections of the South Bohemian Research Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans reportedly turned to the President of the USA with such a wish.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now deposited in the collections of the South Bohemian Research Library.
In a letter, the Germans from Český Krumlov ask the American president not to allow the "Šumava county" - seized by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we really want to be sure that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," reads the letter, signed "People who care about the fate of Šumava."
Since the annexation to Czechoslovakia allegedly gives the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national character - hope only for brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protectorate over Šumava for present and eternal times.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you would cede this territory to a state foreign to us, which oppresses and uproots minorities and has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign their name is allegedly the fear of the revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the U.S. president allegedly doubted the thinking of the Šumava Germans, it was enough for him to hold a referendum in the Šumava county on whether its inhabitants wanted to become part of the USA or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound a bit naïve given today's knowledge of post-war history, according to some eyewitnesses, it aptly illustrates the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Although the Czech Germans must have at least suspected that their expulsion from the republic would take place, only a few of them even admitted such a possibility.
Some expected the United States and Great Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
During the war, as a German from České Budějovice, he was deployed to the navy in the Baltic.
When the British captured him at the end of the war and placed him in a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Czech Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that when they returned home, Czech would come in handy," Chalupa said.
According to him, none of the German prisoners of war living in Czechoslovakia before the war expected to be expelled from the republic on the basis of the Beneš Decrees.
