His boss, the division director, Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, follows the interpretation and occasionally adds to it.
There is enthusiasm and enthusiasm for work.
The seabed hides a hitherto little-known world, rich in natural resources.
You can find oil, ores and other minerals, but also hitherto unknown living organisms that carry the key to the development of a cure for cancer.
Bottom larger than land
Coastal states have now begun to bid vehemently for new underwater territories.
Under the UN Convention, they are exercising their rights, which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the country.
Under the Convention, the latter has exclusive title to all resources of the continental shelf.
"To put it simply, the continental shelf is that part of the seabed and its subsoil that is a natural continuation of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the coastal sea, often beyond the two hundred nautical miles of the so-called exclusive economic zone," Mikulka explains.
The request submitted by the country concerned to the Commission for the delimitation of the external limits of the continental shelf must be supported by extensive scientific and technical documentation based on many costly surveys and measurements.
It is the result of many years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and technical assistance.
The Commission has so far dealt with five requests, namely Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries have succeeded," adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia has recently been the first to substantially expand its underwater possessions.
But he also won New Zealand - the area of seabed granted to him by the commission last week is about 1.6 million square kilometers, roughly six times the size of the state itself.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in the survey.
The future gains from exploiting the seabed will, they promise, be invaluable.
Other States will submit their applications gradually.
They can do so up to ten years after they have ratified the 'UNCLOS'.
Where the continental shelf ends, the area of the ocean floor begins, declared by the convention as the "common heritage of mankind".
Here no state has an exclusive position anymore.
The right to exploit in this area is granted by an international institution established by the Convention.
"But the seabed is no Klondajk," says director Mikulka in exaggeration, adding that his "individual areas are legally clearly defined and their regime is contractually anchored."
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed now belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares them with other countries of the former Eastern Bloc within the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, the country, like investors from a few other states, received the status of a so-called "pioneer investor".
It is authorized to mine in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
