Sleepless Nights for Hypo Real Estate Lenders
As recently as last week, Federal Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück stressed that the German banking system was relatively stable.
It is good that this politician used the word "relatively" and intertwined with the fact that the German banking sector will not be spared from the crisis.
Because that happened last weekend.
Hypo Real Estate (HRE), a financial house monitored by the Dax index, will receive a multi-billion dollar loan from a consortium of German banks to protect against market turbulence.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the loan assistance would go up to 35 billion euros.
Interest will have to be paid by Hypo Real Estate (HRE) only on the amount actually spent.
The money is said to come from private and public banks.
In the background are the losses of the subsidiary Depfa.
According to a newspaper report, the state financier refinanced himself for long-term projects for which he lent money in the extreme short term, which is no longer possible due to mistrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's reserve shrunk by 95% to €2.37 million, and the equity ratio also fell slightly from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Current income and net income from financial transactions fell to zero compared to the previous year, while income from the increased value of claims and certain securities, as well as from the cancellation of provisions for credit trading, fell by more than 70 percent to 5 million euros.
It was only thanks to higher yields from compensation for subsequent settlement costs in the restructuring of the former Depfa Group and from interest compensation under the Tax Code and for intermediation of business for group companies that the sixteen percent decrease in revenues was even more moderate.
After his privatization in 1990, the former state financier burned himself on mortgages for sole traders, which were then separated from the portfolio of services and further managed by Aareal Bank.
Because there was too little to earn in traditional state financing, Depfa was more involved in infrastructure projects and private-public-partnership (PPP) financing and diversified internationally.
Hypo Real Estate must now write off some of its subsidiary's value, and these write-downs will have a "substantial material effect" on the group's profit and loss calculation, as some have vaguely said.
The fact is that the dividend will not.
Already for 2007, it was cut by two-thirds.
Since the takeover of Depf, Hypo Real Estate has been a major financier in state and infrastructure projects.
More strongly than other institutes, it depends on refinancing in the interbank market, since it has no customer deposits.
After the collapse of the US investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the spring of interbank credit has virtually dried up, because banks guard liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs short-term refinancing funds annually for part of Depfa's loan portfolio - about EUR 50 billion.
According to Hypo Real Estate, the group's financial needs are covered by this loan for the foreseeable future and the company is protected "from the influence of international money markets currently largely unable to function".
Other sources have said that this money ensures refinancing by the end of 2009.
On the other hand, HRE Chairman Georg Funke said that Hypo Real Estate Group will not have to use the money markets in the foreseeable future.
The Bundesbank and the Federal Institute for Financial Supervision (BaFin) assume that the competitiveness of the Hypo Real Estate group on the market is now assured.
That is what the bank's shareholders and creditors are hoping for.
But given the dynamics and elusiveness of the crisis, there is probably no certainty.
It is not even completely excluded that the loan would not need to be fully drawn.
However, the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the bank appeared to face insolvency late on Sunday afternoon, even a preliminary bailout will not be able to calm passions.
The share price fell by 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
On the contrary, bond rates held up well.
While senior debt has barely moved, secondary bond rates are losing more significantly.
This applies in particular to bonds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and, logically, bonds maturing after 2009.
Hypo-Real-Estate bonds originally looked like an alternative investment opportunity for speculators, but their stability must be understood depending on the stability of the international financial system after the banking crisis and the crisis of the institute itself, which brought it to the company by taking over Depf.
As long as banks of issue, governments, and less-affected commercial banks are willing to support the system, securities can be counted on to be paid by their maturity date.
But it may also happen what almost no one dares to hope for at the moment: the financial crisis will be overcome in the next 15 months.
But, given the news coming at the same time as this partial nationalization, a probability bordering on certainty has now become a legitimate hope.
This is likely to give long-term creditors a series of sleepless nights to decide whether to give up their obligations.
At the very least, short-term investors can use the cut-off line to convert losses from previous financial years to exchange income of later years for the purpose of future capital gains tax payments.
