Even rats have feelings
When a rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does this mean that they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings.
But how can it be verified whether they feel the same way when they behave like us?
In the Internet journal "Edge" for several years have been published contributions of well-known scientists.
In his series, SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you consider true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it yet, when we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But as soon as we begin to devote ourselves to another kind and open up questions of perception or consciousness in general, we enter impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it will do what many other animals do: pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists infer comparable subjective experiences.
However, I do not believe in that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
This is partly because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always involve the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its contribution to short-term memory and performance or control functions).
This vast area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that humans are different even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity might be hidden in the linguistic nature of man: because so much of his perception is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, surely language would influence it, so that animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably be different from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor analyzed on the basis of our own experience because of special hardware, it presents us with great problems in examining it.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study processes in animal consciousness regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in short-term memory studies in primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But this approach, pursued by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: the two may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this imply for feelings?
I infer them from the fact that an emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as "fear" is the mental state we find ourselves in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) uses operational memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely related to those areas of the cortex that characterize primates, and humans in particular.
In connection with linguistic nature, a subtle gradation of perception arises, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states in order to attribute them to others alongside ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the cortex and brainstem regions dedicated to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it might well contribute to the feelings perceived by multiple animal species.
Purely theoretically, I cannot contradict this, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to us as fear in rats and humans is probably felt equally by both organisms: But how can it be verified, Pankseep says, whether rats and humans feel the same way when they behave in a similar way?
The cockroach flees from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, mere similarity of behavior cannot prove similarity of experience.
It's true that the neural comparison pushes us further: rats and humans have similar brain stems, while cockroaches don't even have brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for feelings?
And even if it could be proven in humans: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how I'm supposed to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and language), I study emotional behavior rather than rat emotional perception.
In any case, in this case, we can see progress at the neural level if we measure the same thing in rats and in humans.
As with rats, I do not study language and consciousness, nor do I examine feelings, because I do not know whether they exist.
It may be considered short-sighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than repeatedly throw myself against the wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
