For years, a mysterious phenomenon has wreaked havoc among scientists - the gravitational slingshot anomaly.
A gravitational slingshot is an aerial maneuver by space probes in which they gain additional momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
Thanks to this, the probes can save a lot of fuel.
The European-American Cassini-Huygens research probe used this physics trick as well as the Ulysses solar probe.
But what has puzzled scientists for years in this case: flying bodies do not behave one hundred percent as one would expect under the good old law of gravity.
On the contrary, there are irregularities in speed.
Probes accelerate or decelerate unexpectedly.
So far, physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They christened it the gravitational slingshot anomaly.
Several experts fear that even Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, which describes the attraction of matter by the curvature of space, might not be entirely correct.
American physicist Stephen Adler of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton remains convinced that Einstein was not wrong, and tries to explain the gravitational slingshot anomaly using so-called dark matter, whose presence in the universe has been detected by astronomers.
"Dark matter could be responsible for this anomaly, which could also be very close to Earth," he writes.
Space explorers have only known about the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
Obviously, a gravitational force emanates from it, the effect of which on other celestial bodies can be observed.
On the contrary, it itself is completely invisible, which means that it does not emit or reflect any electromagnetic radiation, not even visible light.
According to the calculations of scientists, a good fifth of the total mass of the universe is from this dark matter.
