Credit Union Association (BSA) CEO Adrian Coles said it was "humiliating" that credit unions and their members had to pay.
The fourteen billion dollar debt will eventually be repaid by bailing out the Bradford & Bingley mortgages.
However, the interest that accumulates in the meantime will be paid each year by all 700 financial firms that take client deposits.
The Money Services Compensation Plan confirmed to the BBC that all 59 credit unions are included in this figure.
It is humiliating that these institutions, which behaved prudently... Now they have to pay some of the bills of those institutions that were not nearly as prudent
Adrian Coles, BSA
He said that each firm should pay in proportion to the deposits it held, and that credit unions should pay about 18% of the price.
The Treasury estimates that interest on debt will rise to £450 million in 2009.
This means that credit unions will have to find £81 million to pay off the interest from the first year.
Adrian Coles, chief executive of the credit unions trade association, told the BBC he believed it was not fair.
"It is humiliating that those institutions that behaved prudently during the housing boom now have to pay some of the bills of those institutions that were not nearly as prudent."
According to the BSA, no credit union has collapsed since they appeared in 1945.
"We're going to need to look at all aspects of this over the next few weeks to see what options there are to protect credit unions and their members from an account that could be substantial," Cole added.
The interest payable in 2009 covers seven months from the end of September this year to the end of March.
In 2010, interest for the whole year will be to be repaid, and it could be almost twice as much.
Since credit unions are mutual organizations without shareholders, this bill will eventually be paid by their members through higher fees or lower interest rates on their accounts.
Turkey's diplomatic horizons are broadening
Long before Turkey began its bid to join the European Union, the European powers longed to penetrate deep into Turkey's backfield.
On the eastern bank of the Bosphorus, perhaps only twenty paces in Asia, stands one of the finest monuments of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
So that's what tourist guides will tell you.
The building sits astride the end of the platforms, with a tower on each corner of the façade, indistinguishable from a provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once one gets inside the vaulted ticket office, one can no longer doubt the size of the establishment, whose westernmost gate was the station.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which was late in the game of empires, intended to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East with this railway that would lead to Damascus, Baghdad and on to what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their dormitories were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular troops.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone
British and colonial troops advanced out of Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And for the station Hydarpasha also came bad news.
In 1917, an explosion of an ammunition train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has gradually crumbled and history has bypassed it.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
Now a new policy is in place - Turkey is engaged.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To examine the parameters of this new policy, I took a night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, where I was to meet with one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bumpy ride on rails that recalled the old-world rhythms of the famous Night Mail documentary, I arrived in the Turkish capital, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
It aroused suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and metal building deliberately built in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-finished department stores and power dealerships, where middle managers in business suits – both men and women – meet to do early morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry too.
"The goal of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate surroundings.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he told me.
Turkey was cut off from its backfield.
Today they have to look east and west at the same time.
It was no choice.
It had to do both.
"But surely there will come a time," I asked, "when Turkey may have to make a decision?"
"Turkey," he said, "did not want such a decision to have to be made."
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to said almost by heart: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea area, benefit Europe and the United States as much as Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, travel east to Asia and the Middle East on these rails.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Cona, who had watched this building being built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East may now be, in large part, in Turkish hands.
And as I waited at the port for the ferry back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called the "sick man of Europe."
So it seems that, at least then, there was little doubt as to which continent should have a claim to this fascinating country.
Milk will rise by five pence per litre
