New Investigation into U.S. Attorneys Affair
The U.S. Attorney General has appointed a special prosecutor to examine the release of nine U.S. attorneys in 2006.
The move came as a Justice Ministry's chief inspector report on the affair criticized the actions of government officials.
The report criticized White House officials, lawmakers and former Attorney General Alberto Gonzales.
The investigation was sparked by fears that the lawyers had been removed for political reasons.
Special Prosecutor Nora Dannehy will now investigate whether officials questioned during the investigation lied to investigators with the intent to obstruct justice.
Inspector General Glenn Fine said in a report: "Serious allegations, including potential criminal conduct, have not been fully investigated or explained."
