Obscure street, often forgotten and maybe soon for sale
New York City has thousands of roads, streets, highways, and other roads, some famous, others merely utilitarian.
But even many veteran taxi drivers and longtime locals have difficulty finding Extra Place, mostly because they've never heard of it.
This tiny alley is in the East Village neighborhood and runs north from First Street—without getting to Second Street—between Bowery and Second Avenue.
With a width of about ten and a length of forty meters, it looks more like a dusty passage than a traffic route.
There are no street sign signs.
In an ordinary atlas, it is practically invisible.
Nevertheless, the aisle has admirers.
For example, Avalon Bay, the developer of recently built luxury buildings on First Street.
He wants to repave Extra Place and create a cleaner passageway to the shops and boutiques to open in the new buildings.
Other admirers are longtime neighbors who say they were enchanted by the shortened alley simply because it was one of the last remnants of the block before the block was refined.
However, the municipal Office for the Protection and Development of Development, which has the street in its power, has no interest in sticking to it.
At a meeting of the municipal council's land committee, representatives of the municipality and Avalon Bay outlined a plan for the developer to buy the street.
But according to Suzan Stetzer, district manager of Municipal Community 3, the committee favors a scenario where the street remains in the hands of the city and has asked for a new plan, which is expected to be submitted next month.
"The city owns very little land anymore, and we would like to see Extra Place remain in its ownership," she said.
"Proposals could be made for repair and management, which is what Avalon could do, but we also want to guarantee public accessibility."
A few months ago, Avalon Bay announced that it wanted to repave the small street and install seating, several of which would be used by a café whose interest in leasing the space is expected by the developer.
The idea that Avalon Bay could buy the street was first made public at a meeting this month.
Michele de Milly, a spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said that while the company wants to use the street, it doesn't necessarily want to own it.
"The main intention of Avalon Bay is to repair this desolate alley and make it a beautiful place for the public," she said, adding that the sale was proposed by the city.
Seth Donlin, a spokesman for the Office of Conservation and Development, said the city indeed wanted to sell the street, noting that his office's job was to develop the property rather than manage it.
Compared to its more colorful neighbor, the Bowery, Extra Place has left a shallow mark on history.
Some people think the street got its name in 1802, when Philip Minthorne's large farm was divided among several of his children, and no one laid claim to that narrow strip of land.
The back door of CBGB, a punk rock monument that closed in 2006, led into Extra Place, and the alley is perhaps best known as the background photo on the cover of the Ramones album Rocket to Russia.
"The place was amazing," says Danny Fields, the manager of the Ramones who took the photo in November 1976.
"It was full of garbage, torn clothes and pieces of barrels, posters, leaves and rope."
Some locals, including bloggers who write about the improvement of the East Village, oppose the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that the piece of public property, however meager, should remain public.
Others consider Extra Place a rarity - an almost unchanged piece of the city that should be left as it is.
Jeremiah Moss, who writes a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled "The Book of Lamentations: A bitterly nostalgic view of the city in the process of extinction"), posted part of the Extra Place story from the Talk About the City column that appeared in The New Yorker in 1952.
The author of the article, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a narrow cul-de-sac, dark even by day and bordered by rusty iron warehouse doors and knocked-down windows where week-old newspapers run through ditches."
With a few exceptions, the alley one recent evening looked exactly the same.
The rat ran across the blind end of the street near the door that once led to the CBGB, where an expensive clothing store now stands.
There was graffiti on the walls, and next to a fresh batch of discarded newspapers lay an empty beer bottle.
A few passers-by said they rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested that they might find a boost useful.
Fields, on the other hand, said he thinks some people underestimate the impact of the alley in its current state.
"The best years of my life," he said, "were in places dark, damp, and disgusting."
The Bilingual Debate: Immersion in English
In this issue of Education in Focus, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss candidates' attitudes toward bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a California scholar and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of "Worse Than You Think: Why Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools."
Effectively reaching Hispanic voters is a tricky business.
Barack Obama's education agenda proves it.
The Obama campaign notes that "African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students," which is true.
To combat such performance gaps, Obama's education agenda is particularly advocating, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for those just learning English.
But the question for Barack Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in narrowing performance gaps.
Consider Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in Los Angeles East County.
The students of this school are in the vast majority of cases Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Despite this, in the state tests in mathematics in 2008, an incredible hundred percent of fourth-graders reached the highest level.
Almost as amazing ninety-three percent of fourth-graders ranked highest on state tests in English language and literature.
This incredible success was achieved by a different method than Obama's preferred method.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of abilities, and an approach without excuses.
Further, and Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, principal of Sixth Street, the school's pedagogical approach is "complete immersion" for those just learning English.
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Miss Mikels, who is opposed to bilingual education, told me, "We've had tremendous success with one brand new student from Mexico – after twelve months you'd walk into a classroom and not know which one it is."
"It works," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for what other schools with large proportions of Hispanic and English-language students should look like?
The school's performance should make the answer to this question a given, but his own party's educational agenda (the National Education Association is a longtime proponent of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make it obscure the prediction of Obama's answer.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue when he said people should stop worrying about "English-only" laws.
Instead, "you should ensure that your children speak Spanish," he said.
If Obama really wants to close the performance gap, he should think carefully about educational models that work, rather than ridicule and trivialize them.
