Wild ride in the second quarter broke the team's record
After spending more than anyone else in a Jets jersey over the past eight seasons, defensive player Shaun Ellis thought he'd seen it all.
Then, on Sunday, he watched the second quarter unfold, in which the Jets turned a pointless game into a graceful drive.
"I've never seen anything like it," Ellis said.
The second quarter began after the Jets and Arizona Cardinals matched the gloomy clouds above them with their troubled play.
Then quarterback Brett Favre sent Laveranues Coles on a twelve-yard touchdown sprint, perfectly foreshadowing an afternoon in which their gradually developing relationship moved forward by miles.
Favre sent Coles in that quarter for two more touchdowns, including one in which he dropped a cornerback, and another 10 seconds before the half.
"It wasn't anything out of the ordinary," Favre said of all his passes to Coles.
"He's a damn good player.
We communicated well, no matter what people think."
While Favre and Coles were tossing, the defense was attacking Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner.
Cornerback Darelle Revis intercepted a stray throw and put it back 32 yards for a touchdown.
Safety Eric Smith picked up another pass and intercepted it.
Linebacker David Bowens forced Warner into a fumble.
The last loss of the ball, the fumble that Bowens forced, was perhaps the best ever.
The Cardinals got to the ball 10 seconds before the end, and after the Jets got the ball back, Jay Feely kicked a 20-yard goal from the field to give him a 34-0 lead.
That's the most the Jets have ever scored in a single quarter.
Jets coach Eric Mangini, when asked to describe the madness, said, "Second quarter or third quarter?"
When told that both — the Jets allowed 21 points in the third quarter without a response — Mangini said, "I can tell you that I enjoyed the second quarter a lot more than the third.
A lot of points were scored in a short period of time."
Rested Gebreselassie improves his world record
Ethiopia's Haile Gebreselassie once again showed why many consider him the best long-distance runner ever when he broke his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday to become the first person to run a 26.2-mile race under two hours and four minutes.
By winning on a pleasantly flat track in 2:03:59, he beat by 27 seconds his previous time of 2:04:26, which he ran last year in Berlin.
Gebreselassie, who is 35, has set the 26th world record of his career, which is truly incredibly broad - he has broken the world record or at least is the world champion at all distances from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebreselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic Marathon because he feared - perhaps too alarmed in retrospect - that air pollution would irritate his asthma problems.
Instead, he promised to run in Berlin.
In near-perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - Gebreselassie won on Sunday with a lightning-fast average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As track runners like Gebreselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya focused on longer distances, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the past decade since Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebreselassie told reporters that he had calf cramps two weeks ago and missed a week of training.
The break had obviously excited him rather than delayed him.
"I'm so happy," Gebreselassie told reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
A week ago I started again and I was a bit doubtful today, but everything was fine."
He was also criticized - particularly in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for over-planning his races, generally avoiding the world's top marathons, relying on conductors as if it were a race on the track, and putting world records above the sense of competition.
But this criticism can hardly diminish Gebreselassie's tremendous running qualities.
Kept pace by four Kenyans, Gebreselassie reached the halfway point in 1:02:04.
After they fell off, Gebreselassie was constantly chased by two elite Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi.
A little earlier than three miles from the finish, Gebreselassie took one last step and escaped Kwambai, who then finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German citizen, finished an excellent year with the seventh fastest time in history of 2:19:19.
The record time of 2:15:25 is held by Paula Radcliffe from Great Britain.
Thirty-six-year-old Mikitenko surprisingly won the London Marathon last spring in a time of 2:24:14.
She skipped the Beijing Games due to what was described as a back injury, but she recovered and won in Berlin, improving her personal best by almost five minutes in the third marathon she has ever run.
She ran the race cleverly and thoughtfully: she let four Ethiopian and Kenyan runners run away to a big lead and then caught them after about 18 1/2 miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
Pride and obstacles to the life of blacks in a separate city
Tucked away among the sprawling theme parks of greater Orlando, a few miles away from everything shiny, noisy and huge, lies a quiet city in which the pride and demands of African-American life come alive.
Eatonville, the first completely black town to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools, and no prison."
Now it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to Eatonville's annual Zora! festival to pay tribute to Hurston, Harlem's most famous female writer.
The city she described remains aloof, even though she made it a stopover for tourists by including it in a Florida tourist guide created by the Depression-era Federal Writers project.
It is still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the thirties, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open debate about race, many residents remain wary of the views of strangers.
"We pay a lot of attention to how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and toil.
It is both a historical model of black rise and a community of nearly 2400 people, where the poverty rate is double the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also a dub-shaded example of Southern, rural black culture—sometimes despised, sometimes praised—that grew out of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the locals are both proud and protective.
And the concern about the idea of Eatonville really began with Zora, which is the only way Hurston is called here.
She introduced the world to her hometown through heartfelt books full of dialects such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of a Florida tourist guide turned the city just short of Highway 17, which runs through downtown Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With the beat of a big drum in life and literature, Hurston led readers into the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"To the left of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown-decorated modern national school with well-kept yards and playgrounds, always looked after by Howard Miller, though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned Widow Dasha's new husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits into a one-hour hotel."
So, in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
This was clearly not a typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora said it like it was," says ninety-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the choir of Johnson Girls, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered as a lively eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time, when she rushed into town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today prides itself on dressing with dignity.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many sneered.
"People were always happy to see Zora," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed very long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were taken out of print.
Eatonville, along with the rest of the world, seemed to have forgotten it.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the twenties of the 20th century, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings at Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood her importance to the world or her legacy," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography "Wrapped in Rainbows."
The change came in the 80s of the 20th century.
Orange County officials wanted to extend a five-lane highway through the city instead of Kennedy Boulevard, the city's two-lane main road.
Orlando's sprawl has already pushed Interstate Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still emerging from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the fifties of the 20th century, the struggle for mixing races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At the time, a bunch of white guys, they came and threw oranges and things at people who were sitting on the side," Franklin said.
"We actually had one lady who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration, calling its decision in Brown v. the Education Chamber "offensive rather than glorifying to my race."
Residents now say school desegregation, while positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of local youth.
"Black kids were used to hugs — I remember — you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until the teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You're not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher — I mean, there's a cultural barrier," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped make room for many other Zora Neala Hurston — black writers, actors, and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with reckless self-confidence and quotes such as "How can anyone deny himself the pleasure of my presence!
I don't get it."
In 1975, Alice Walker arrived at Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, Robert E. Hemenway's vaunted biography of Hurston hit bookstore shelves and re-placed her in the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville's most famous daughter found the ramp lights again.
Hurston's former neighbors now saw her as a savior.
To show what the state can destroy with its highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return to celebrate.
After several years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"Those five lanes of highway have resurrected, you would say they blew up, real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped change the city's image.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the church in 1993, began to show up in greater numbers, and residents began to reassess the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historic Registry in 1998.
The new one-story library (named, of course, after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the re-asphalted and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with only 27 black families in the eighties of the 19th century.
(Today, 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come in search of the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required in advance, and certain items — such as white-painted murals in Eatonville's oldest church depicting blacks in fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a brave, confident teacher who likes deep reds, still worry that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as Hurston's festival has grown, so has domestic pride.
Young people, especially, tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled and all, but no better, not worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
Franklin's nephew, eighteen-year-old Edwin Harvey, voices a genuine love for the community as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or the police, which he says would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as eleven-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just drive through here, think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to the others,'" Alondra Kenon said recently Sunday after the church.
"But if you really stop and look at the history for a moment, it's a very nice city."
Here in New York, we are all fluent financially
At first glance, nothing has changed here.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from newsstands and giant TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn't realize they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never have guessed that in the glass beehive of offices overhead, bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York have their worst "bad day in the office" since the 1929 crisis.
Messengers still rattle metal carts on the sidewalks and carry muffin roasters to breakfast meetings.
Hispanics still move between tower blocks and wear, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts that hang from the rockers on their backs.
Office rats are still queuing for their morning bagel at street food stalls, and it's still impossible to get a yellow taxi between four and seven in the afternoon on a weekday.
It didn't look like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to open a savings account on Thursday afternoons.
Even though I had timed this task to coincide with the late afternoon siesta at my local JP Morgan Chase office, there were already about twenty people waiting in line.
Not in front of checkout windows to pick up or deposit cash, but in front of the counter where older clients order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy's general store, and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker," came for the same reason I did.
But unlike me, they have already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in places where they came, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They took money from so-called thrifts (somewhat similar to building societies), money associations, and those types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state and which claim to look after their customers like a family.
In the past year, 15 such banks have quietly failed.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and as New Yorkers returned home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, tried to hunt down a rescue buyer.
The office and shop staff who stood in front of me, fearing another collapse, were moving their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe haven and that does most of the bailouts on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have become fluent in finance over the past week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket was talking on the phone and talking about Lehman Borthers, the failed bank, and its emaciated chief executive, Dick Fulda, with the familiarity of a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed caretaker of my apartment building in her fifties, changed the subject of our ordinary conversation—Brad, Angelina, or my grocery delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me, "I now have my savings in money market funds.
I've moved it, I'm not going to take any chances."
Memorable Lives: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's music director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (obituary, September 11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
As part of the district music plan, he founded the excellent youth choir Proteus a year later.
He was supposed to be 21, but by the time Proteus sang for the last time in 1979, a few of us were nearly 30 – we simply refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (mythological shapeshifter) represented the willingness and ability of the choir to embark on any music presented to it - whether madrigals or Messiaen, either alone or with a full orchestra.
The musical adaptability created by such a young choir was often overwhelming, always exciting, and all thanks to the inspiration of this one man and a passion for music that remained absolutely constant throughout.
How often did Tod tell us to "let the music speak for itself."
He said, "A composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the music.
So sing it! "
His baton technique was crystal clear and precise, but it was neither dictatorial nor flowery.
Wherever the musical standard was, it always raised it.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor was to be knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well in the two decades when he conducted the Guildford Philominsky from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past 40 years or so, I have reviewed more than 100 of his concerts, and I can honestly say that I have never been disappointed with any of them - and have been inspired many times.
Tod Handley had such a great combination of size and personal modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply "dragged one or two soaked songs around the world."
Many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (September 25) states that "in 1946 he returned to economic history at Oxford, and in 1950 he became a researcher at Houblon-Norman... and at the same time studied at BSc, MA and PhD".
This is based on Woodruff's author's note in Beyond Nab End, but it's not accurate.
From 1946 to 1953 he taught economic history at the University of Nottingham, at which time he completed his dissertation on the British rubber industry, supervised by Professor J. D. Chambers, which was subsequently published in 1958 as The British Rubber Industry.
He actually spent 1950-51 in America as a researcher at Houblon-Norman and the summer of 1952 at the Universities of Illinois, Harvard, and New York.
In 1953, he finally left Nottingham for Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff switched to this part of his career.
Muslim graves desecrated after Austria's right-wing fault
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, of the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party take part in a rally that presented the organization "Cities Against Islamization" in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry signs similar to road signs that show mosques crossed out with a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend in which far-right parties made huge gains in the general election.
More than 90 graves in a cemetery in the town of Traun near Linz were badly damaged sometime between Friday evening and this morning, and police believe it was an organised event.
The culprits spray-painted Jewish symbols such as the Star of David on some graves, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to disguise the extremists' motives of hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether the incident was in any way linked to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by reports of desecration as the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan drew to a close.
Austria, meanwhile, is entering a soul-searching round after swinging right in yesterday's parliamentary election.
The two far-right parties, which together won more than 30 percent of the vote, the Freedom Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, have waged vehement anti-immigration campaigns, with some of their slogans denounced as xenophobic by critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, leader of the Freedom Party, which won more than 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against headscarves and burqas and even expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived to be related to Islam.
At a recent meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses conducted immediately after the elections, which have positioned the extreme right as the country's strongest political bloc, suggest that this change was mainly due to young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed to go on a trip abroad
Gary Glitter, a glam rock star convicted of sexually abusing children, was banned from travelling to France and Spain.
Officials imposed the six-month ban on Glitter after he informed monitoring authorities that he planned to travel via France to Spain.
Kent Police approved the travel ban last Thursday after handing over evidence of Glitter's past child sexual abuse convictions.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford Lowest Criminal Court in Kent, but was represented by lawyers from Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the Courts Service said: "On Thursday 25 September, at Ashford Lowest Criminal Court, Kent Police applied for an injunction that would prevent Mr Paul Gadd from crossing the border into France and Spain until 25 March.
Paul Gadd did not attend in person."
Glitter, 64, informed authorities that he wished to travel abroad, as required by his sex assault record.
He must notify the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
They must also hand over the scheduled departure date to the police a week in advance.
If he neglected to inform the authorities, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent Police said it would not be hearing individual cases of Glitter's possible trips around the county.
A Kent Police spokeswoman said: "Kent Police will do everything necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our point of view, it is easier to track someone who stays in the UK because we have extensive systems that manage potential dangers more effectively.
Protecting the people of Kent is a top priority for Kent Police and we are working diligently to monitor the behaviour of recorded sexual assaulters to minimise any danger to the public."
Glitter returned to Britain last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two girls, aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, he flew to Bangkok to board a flight to London.
But he said he was not feeling well and refused to fly to London.
Thai authorities did not let him pass through passport control and eventually flew to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also refused to allow him entry, and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and immigration officials insisted on his return to Britain.
On 22 August, he finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 and stayed there while his solicitor, David Corker, went to Uxbridge's lowest criminal court in west London and at the same time Scotland Yard successfully requested an order requiring him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter was previously imprisoned for four months in the UK for possession of child pornography.
A Home Office source said Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, was calm and glad that Glitter had been prevented from travelling to France and Spain.
"To capture the real character, I photograph the master off stage." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no ruffles or costumes.
Only the essence of the great flamenco masters, detached from concentrating on interpretation - this is the only way to achieve a relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other - man.
Inseparable, apart from privacy, in those moments away from the audience - then one can see the intimate gesture, the depth of a fleeting glance, or the passionate gesticulation of hands that are carefree because they are not about to step on stage.
In "Flamenco-people", the German Günther Bauer alternates the theatricality of performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer compiles a unique iconography of flamenco from different environments.
The exhibition, which runs as part of the Month of Flamenco Photography (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca) program, "reflects the ever-growing international importance of flamenco," says the author, explaining that "Flamenco-people" "can be any people, but if you look at the photographs, you will find that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists capable of bringing passion, sadness, joy to the scene... and completely captivate the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
They carry their personality and character within.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that allows me to capture the personality of flamenco greats.
Fascinated by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to portray flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
The use of different stylistic means contradicts the classical basis of the film and lends it a contemporary spirit, an idea that, according to Bauer himself, is also reflected in flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, but which does not cease to surprise and evolve."
What captivates the audience is not the effect of the dance, singing or play itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we encounter the most essential, that spirit that reveals itself in the way of perceiving, being and experiencing, has been a constant in the work presented during these days in the El Fotómata gallery.
This selection of nearly seventy photographed artists is shaped by well-known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyoso, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo, among others.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco and will soon be published in a book containing exhibited portraits.
Two years ago, Bauer's passion for portraiture led him to the idea of repeating the idea in "Portraits of Sporty Vintage Cars" ("SportARTproject").
Although their concept is different from "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "photographing people, getting to know them and being able to enter their lives for a moment, whether longer or just briefly, is my passion.
I think in photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
A person meets or meets people, personalities that he sometimes does not even know, or they give him only a few minutes to take pictures.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer I always try to realize my ideas."
A collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco entitled "Flamenco-people" is exhibited in the El Fotómata Gallery at 20 rue de la Mata, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
Vargas Llosa admitted that the novel he was writing was "audacious."
It takes place in an environment that he does not yet know, and tells about events unknown to him, yet Mario Vargas Llosa intends to successfully realize his new project - he is currently working on a novel whose main character is Roger Casemant, an Irish nationalist who lived for twenty years in the Congo and traveled in the Amazon.
The perennial favorite for the Nobel Prize in Literature admitted yesterday at the Hay Festival Segovia that the project that currently employs him "is presumptuous" and that "everything indicates that I should not write" this novel.
"If I had sense, I wouldn't do it, but I will do it and I believe that one day I will finish it," he concluded his speech at the festival of exchange of ideas, thoughts and words, which over the course of four days saw around a hundred writers, historians and journalists and thousands of other people in the city of the aqueduct.
The author of the novel "The City and the Dogs" was one of the main characters of the third year of the Feast of the Word and fulfilled expectations.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival Award for Most Popular Writer — an old edition of Dickens' "Our Mutual Friend" — filled the Juan Bravo Theater to the last place.
With Félix Romeo introducing it, he had before him a resigned audience to whom an hour of time passed like water - the Peruvian recalled with astonishing precision and a good dose of humor how from the original "incredible adventure" of "the pleasure of the passionate reader" and from "the power to live more than I have lived" a literary mission was born in him; how he substitutes for "lack of inspiration" by writing "disciplined", carefully collecting the text, correcting and rewriting; or how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas influenced his writing, and what "memory images" are the basis of his stories.
The Hispano-American novelist admitted that "there is no way" to know if and to what extent books can change lives, "but I refuse to believe that literature is just entertainment, a fleeting experience" - Vargas Llosa emphasized, adding that according to him "they affect people" and "make them try to stand out of line", and urged writers not to "succumb to frivolity" and "take responsibility" of their mission.
