'May Blood' ('Sangre de mayo'), Garcia's epic bet
José Luis Garci's Sangre de mayo, inspired by Benito Pérez Galdós's Episodes from the National Past, revives the famous uprising of the Spanish against the French – the most ambitious film in his filmography with a budget of around €15 million.
In this way, the filmmaker wanted to "portray the eloquence of the characters and the analysis of society" that he had always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today together with Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría during the presentation of the film in front of a large team of performers.
May Blood, with over two and a half hours of footage, will be released this Friday, and a more than four-hour series for Telemadrid television is planned in the future.
As a great admirer of the literary work of Galdós, José Luis Garci claims that he fulfilled his "childhood dream" by making this film, thanks to Esperanza Aguirre, who three years ago commissioned him to make a film for the bicentenary of the Autonomous Province of Madrid on May 2, and he accepted the offer, saying that the plot would be based on Episodes of the National Past.
The budget of 15 million, to which the province of Madrid contributed in its entirety, represents for Garcia a "unique opportunity" to create an environment with sets and costumes corresponding to the image of "a trembling Spain that was mistaken into a leader to fight for – the struggle for independence led to the decline and backwardness of the country during the reign of Ferdinand VII," he said.
However, the director regrets that he cannot count on the financial support received for Ala Triste or Goya's Ghosts - almost double the size of May Blood - so he could not shoot some scenes from the script signed at the same time by Horacio Valcárcel, with whom he has worked for almost his entire film career.
The director of "To Start Over" (Volver and the Empezar) works as he is used to - on the set together with the actors with whom he usually rehearses before shooting and whom he does not choose by casting because he finds it "humiliating" and also believes that "part of the director's profession is, among other things, to go to theaters and cinemas and thus learn what is happening in the craft,  which it deals with".
Many of the actors he chose for Blood in May appear in front of his camera several times, such as Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga and Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
Garci, with four Oscar nominations, one of which he won, is of the opinion that none of the three candidates representing Spain this year before the Hollywood Academy, May Blood alone, Seven Tables of French Billiards and the last selected Blind Sunflowers, represent the younger generation of the Spanish film scene, but claims that "it is yet to be seen."
