Isabel Bayón revives the spiritual legacy of Seville dancer Tórtola Valencia
A Seville flamenco dancer will pay tribute to another Seville dancer.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia, from a Catalan father (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and an Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in Triana, and moved with her family to London when she was three years old.
She danced modern dance and focused on oriental dances.
She lived a life full of passion, pioneering women's emancipation like Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf and Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian and fought for the abolition of the corset, which prevented women from moving freely.
Isabele Bayón was enchanted by Isabele Bayón's life influenced by the dance and aesthetic revolution of interwar Europe.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this character to me – it seemed unbelievable to me."
According to the dancer, "We are not interested in telling her life, but in grasping the soul.
The titles of her dance performances reminded me of the rhythms of flamenco.
So the "butterfly dance" reminded me of the guajira or the "snake dance" of some tango.
Her dancing was sensual and they told me that my dance also corresponds to that aesthetic," she says.
The performance counts on the involvement of two exceptional personalities: Miguel Veda, who will sing to Isabelle in one performance as in "The Open Door" (La puerta abierta), and dance teacher Matilde Coral, who made an exception and agreed to cooperate with her former pupil.
"Matilde represents the elder Tortola, a mature figure.
