Honda will attack for the second time with its bestseller
In November, Honda will launch the second-generation Jazz.
If the predecessor of this single-box vehicle already had a lot of space, it now offers an even more spacious interior.
Added to this are improved engines that increase driving comfort and allow greater fuel economy.
Evolution rather than revolution.
This is the second generation Honda Jazz.
Although from an aesthetic point of view the lines of the new Jazz are very similar to the previous model, there have been many changes to this single-box car.
Examples include innovative design, a new platform, larger dimensions and new engines.
Even before we examine the new model, it should be noted that the new Jazz comes to the market six years after the launch of the first generation.
Therefore, the first thing we notice is that Honda needed a shorter period than other manufacturers to rejuvenate this model.
Although the Jazz is a lesser-known model in Europe, it has become a phenomenon in other markets.
This is the case in Japan, the country where the Jazz was the best-selling car in 2002, and also during this year 2008.
It is in Japan that almost a million units have been sold since the launch of the Honda Jazz.
The second market was the old continent with approximately half a million units sold in six years.
Honda, however, aims for the new Jazz to increase sales in its category.
Thus, while in 2007 the Japanese company sold a total of 83,000 units of the Honda Jazz, in 2009 estimates put the number of 100,000 cars in the European market, which would represent an increase of 17% in the European market.
In the Spanish market, Honda has sold a total of 8,000 units of the Jazz since 2002, representing 6.7% of Honda's total sales in Spain.
As for the new generation of Jazz, the management of the Spanish branch expects sales of 2,000 units for the full year.
The arrival of the new Jazz will allow Honda to significantly mitigate the decline in sales in Spain.
The carmaker's management thus de facto expects to end the year with a total of 22,000 units sold, which means 4,000 fewer than in 2007 and a decrease of 16%.
Despite this increase in sales, Honda increased its share of the Spanish market to 1.8%, up from 1.6% last year.
In 2010, the Japanese firm expects to reach 2%.
To achieve this share, Honda is counting on the success of its next new model.
It is the Honda Insight, a five-door hybrid of a compact size with a length of 4.37 meters, from which the Japanese company expects worldwide sales of approximately 200,000 units per year.
In terms of markets, according to estimates by the Japanese manufacturer, 50% of Insight will be sold in the United States, while the remaining percentage will be split between the old continent and Japan.
The Honda Insight is expected to go on sale in the first months of next year, when it is presented to the public in Valencia in January.
Compared to the first generation, all dimensions of the new Jazz have increased.
Its length has increased up to 3.9 meters (five centimeters more), width to 1.69 meters (two centimeters more) and wheelbase to 2.5 meters, which means an extension of five centimeters.
The height, on the other hand, has not changed and is still 1.52 meters.
By increasing the dimensions, the interior space was also enlarged.
This advantage was achieved both by using a new platform and by storing the fuel tank in the middle of the car, which had already been used in the previous Honda Jazz.
The luggage compartment volume - which has a double bottom system - has also increased to 399 litres, 19 litres more than the luggage compartment volume of the first generation.
It should be noted that these dimensions occur in the version with the 1.4 engine, since the luggage compartment volume of the Honda Jazz 1.2 is 379 liters.
In addition to exterior features such as LED rear lights and the possibility of fitting a panoramic glass roof, another improvement is easier access to the rear seats.
Doors leading to the second row of seats allow an opening angle of 80 degrees, compared to 67 for the first Jazz.
The engines are also new to the second-generation Honda Jazz.
Initially, this small model will be offered with two 1.2 and 1.4-liter petrol engines.
Both engines use i-VTEC technology, which enables lower fuel consumption, lower carbon dioxide emissions and delivers excellent powertrain upgrades along with high torque over the full engine speed range.
The first 1.2-liter engine has a power of 90 hp at 6,000 rpm with a maximum torque of 114 Nm at 4,900 rpm.
This engine - which had 78 hp in the previous generation Jazz - has a consumption of 5.3 liters and emissions of 125 grams of CO2.
Compared to the previous engine, which reached 83 hp in the previous generation, the current one will reach 100.
Honda Jazz 1.4 with 100 hp has a combined consumption of 5.4 liters and emissions of 128 grams of CO2.
