"Auto bee" prevents collisions
This time, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, specifically bees, to advance the development of accident protection technologies.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes as a model the flying of bees and thus prevents collisions.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C, which represents the first step in collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Center for Technical Advancement developed the robot in collaboration with the Center for Advancement in Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, general manager of public relations for technology, research and development for the brand, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four safety shield zones.
The robot is tasked with strengthening the collision avoidance capability of cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which closely resembles a Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the compound bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, which allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
Engineers designed what they called a Laser Range Finder to create this visual feature.
It records obstacles up to two meters away from a radius of 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it into a collision warning.
"The moment an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the bee's movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to a right or even greater angle to avoid a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobile Lab and Chief Engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, a robot cannot move up and down or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and the direction in which it is enabled by the rotation of its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as in bees.
In addition to accelerating and decelerating, Nissan used the rotation function to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The device only needs to process information every few seconds and act on that data.
It does not require the retention of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, thanks to which it can operate without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we're not talking about giga or mega."
This is the first step in the development of new immediate collision avoidance technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be used in production cars in a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to incorporate a unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination while avoiding obstacles on the way.
Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will need to install an "alcolock"
The Home Office requires a driver with three administrative penalties for drink-driving to install a system in his car to prevent him from starting the car while drunk or if he is out of breath.
The proposal became known in June this year and is now included in the annual report of the Prosecutor General's Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for one year.
Its aim is to get the driver back behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to undergo a course of traffic re-education.
In addition to the National Traffic Safety Authority, the General Directorate of Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for Automobile Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of motorists charged more than once for drunk driving get behind the wheel again.
Alcolock should prevent this, as it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver has not breathed before or if a higher than permitted alcohol concentration is recorded.
Its price exceeds €1 000 and would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study to this effect carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that offences on vehicles equipped with this device decreased by 65% during the first year after their introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address such conduct before it results in a criminal offence.
And to help introduce it, since legislation can be done in the usual way, the necessary modification of the criminal provisions requires a change in the law.
The device is not yet available in any retail version on the Spanish market, although it has already been installed on a trial basis in some industrial and utility vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on a proposal by the PSOE (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party) recommending the installation of this system in school buses, as is the case in France.
