Talking in your sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don't mean the ones who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but the kids who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may startle you, but in reality it is meaningless.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somnilokvia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely more than one of you has been told that he spoke in his sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single reason to explain its onset.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night demons, enuresis nocturne or sleepwalking, but this does not have to be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often accompany very high fevers, stressful or agitated situations.
In any case, this is a little-understood phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or vice versa (screams, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great force, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if he has any problem that causes great anxiety in him and manifests itself in this way.
We have said that it is a harmless disorder, so it is not treated unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
However, what we can do is keep in mind some very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to upset the baby too much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who find it difficult to relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When somniloknie appears, try to keep calm.
Remind yourself that she is harmless to the child and that he will not remember anything of what happened the next day.
Useful advice
Don't be him.
It's useless because he's not conscious and you'll interrupt his sleep.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps and therefore rests.
Remember that if you feel distressed several times in a row, it would be a good idea to seek advice or find out what causes such anxiety in your child.
If he understands what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to interrogate him and extract information from him.
It will be of no use, because when he sleeps, he is not conscious to organize his thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming about, and therefore why he is saying it, so be very careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you reach.
Never tell your child that you can ask him about his secrets at night.
Not even for fun.
This causes great anxiety.
Just don't worry, it's not a bad thing, it's just an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
