Interview - Blood that is certain again
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly happy because Héma-Québec had become one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained the trust of the public, which was seriously shaken after the contaminated blood scandal in the 80s and 90s.
As is widely known, the state blood reserve managed by the Transfusion Department of the Canadian Red Cross was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 80s.
In view of this drama and a wave of public outrage, the Canadian government opened a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not happen again.
While Judge Krever hesitated to submit the report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this role was played by the Gélineau Committee.
After the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Heme-Québec, which was to farm Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Company to supply all the provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," Dr. Décary recalls.
"The situation was disheartening.
Through continuous efforts to improve the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area over the following years, we have regained the public's trust," he says, proudly adding that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population trusted Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile."
Since its founding on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"At that time, we saw the emergence of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," says the woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread through the blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which, where we do not know and where the spread of a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterised by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, is at stake.
In April 1999, therefore, we refused blood from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the precautionary principle made sense."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood, rather than the antibodies on which the tests used previously were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period between when a patient is infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood with our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without them knowing it and without being able to find out.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of acquiring AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone becomes infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through the blood product to appear.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary for recovery," says the head of the management of Héma-Québek.
"The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what disease-causing element may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by insect bites.
We need to be cautious at all times," Dr. S. Smith continues. Décary emphasizes that in addition to secure supplies, Héma-Québec must also count on sufficient supplies.
"Needs are growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for donation."
However, any healthy person at least 18 years old, meeting the criteria of admissibility, can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people offering blood are not accepted because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have visited a country where mud fever is raging, they are excluded for a year.
"With this 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be supplemented as they age and can no longer donate blood.
But convincing people to donate blood is difficult, especially to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life today is so unbridled that we rarely find an hour to donate blood," laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Heme-Quebec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, is rich in stem cells, which can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample into the bank, and we expect to collect over a thousand a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," says Dr. Décaryová, who describes the umbilical cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some moms are disappointed that they can't access it," because Héma-Québec doesn't have enough resources to offer this complex and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
