"From Godbout, who founded Hydro-Québec, to Lesage, who carried out the Peaceful Revolution and nationalization of hydroelectricity, to Bourassa, who created James Bay, our party has been able to shape the future," said Jean Charest.
At the press conference, he appealed to another authority, this time conservative, namely John Diefenbaker's "Roads to the North" program, prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
When it came to the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam, Charest pointed out that its launch is planned for 2012.
"I'm only saying it between us, but I plan to be there," he confided to his membership, eliciting considerable applause.
The same prime minister who said in April that there would be no elections in 2008, and undoubtedly not even in 2009, has not ruled out the possibility of calling elections in the autumn of this year, which is allowed by law.
However, he stressed that his schedule is packed, especially the Federal Council's mission to China and the Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend congress provided the Liberal leader with a platform for some nationalist resolutions, especially certain "efforts to amend the constitution," which passed very smoothly: the PLQ (Liberal Party of Quebec) demanded in particular recognition of the "specificity of Quebec" in the Constitution.
He also wants Quebec to appoint a portion of the members of Canada's Broadcasting Council who would have veto power over decisions taken in Quebec.
On the part of the opposition, Plan North was received with scepticism in its main features.
PQ (Parti Québecois) leader Pauline Marois has re-launched the Northern Development Policy of Quebec, launched by the Landry government in 2001.
According to her, when the Liberal government came to power in 2003, it renounced this policy.
If she had stuck to it, "we would be further away today," Marois remarked alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (where elections are held today), Françoise Mercure.
ADQ said it would support the government's adoption of Plan North.
"But we want it to be more than just theatre," explained Sébastien Proulx, the leader representing Mario Dumont, who is returning from the holidays today.
Letters - Disgraced country
It was Vic Toews, the former Minister of "Justice" (oh irony) in Harper's cabinet, who dared to call Louise Arbour a "disgrace" to Canada last summer.
To humiliate a woman who has waged a relentless fight for justice and who deserves all our admiration says a lot about the Prime Minister's entourage and Stephen Harper himself.
We have before us a government which, as the only one of all the Western countries involved, has not repatriated a national locked up in the Guantánamo concentration camp.
A government that takes no account of the fact that Omar Khadr was a young adolescent at the time of the alleged acts to take place.
The only government that, despite Canada being a signatory to the Geneva Convention, denies its word and leaves a child soldier to rot in inhumane conditions.
The only one that relies on a parody of justice to assess the guilt of the accused.
UNICEF, Amnesty International and, in particular, the Canadian Bar Association are advocating the repatriation of Omar Khadr so that he can have a fair trial in Canada.
The same government closes its eyes to torture: it cares little that this young man is psychologically destroyed in the future, and no doubt permanently, after so many years of torture.
We don't realize it, but we are witnessing the creeping erosion of our rights, our freedom, and our "democracy," a word that Harper brandishes and that sounds so empty from his mouth.
The time has come when there is no longer any morality: it is possible to torture a Canadian citizen, mistreat him, imprison him at the whim of the head of the hitherto minority government (as will be the case after October 14...).
Many voters believe that they will find salvation in a party that preaches Virtue, Law and Order: they do not see that this government has renounced what constituted the reputation and dignity of our country.
The shame, Mr Toews, is in this renunciation and not elsewhere.
Opinions - The Orwellian Discourse of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched a libel prosecution of three authors and a poor small publisher in order to provoke a "transparent public debate" and demands six million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the law that judges truthfulness, especially in the case of libel prosecutions.
Unsurprisingly, Garver misses this crucial distinction entirely.
Or is Barrick Gold's best way to conduct public debate to bankrupt anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend and fight in a very uneven battle against an army of lawyers supported by the mine's almost bottomless pockets.
Indeed, the tactic in these unbalanced struggles often consists in ruining the defendants in order to enforce conciliation that shuts the mouths of the opposing party and, moreover, frightens anyone who dares to pursue the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view to public opinion.
Contrary to what happens in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada the debate is normally about exchanging ideas rather than blowing with a baton.
The mining companies therefore had no choice but to open up their books, their documentation, and to spark a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the matter.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have confidence in public opinion and is quick to reject petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he could demand "public debate" while contemptuous the views of the same public?
In the vice president's world, the word seems to refer only to boldly paid attorneys, and not to all Canadians; This is a rather narrow conception of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand—or does not want to understand—that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because it rejects the mining company's brutal ways.
The public is ready to listen to Barrick and judge the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant's mouth is to be shut (as part of its prosecution of the "public debate", Barrick, by the way, has just filed an official notice to the authors of Noir Canada to officially tell them to stop using the term...).
Garver's surreal speech aside, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university's freedom of inquiry and search for truth, which are essential to any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to cite reliable sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it becomes impossible to study and discuss topics that the world's rich companies dislike without exposing ourselves to repeated prosecution, who else will?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have done so if it had followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has the right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's over-the-top lawsuit makes it clear that, despite what it claims, it has no appetite for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to curb this type of wrongful prosecution.
Operation to save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand each other
Yesterday, the Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally agreed on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the thirties.
A new version of the $700 billion plan to contain the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of its application by elected representatives, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public money deposited, new measures for capturing the number of homes foreclosed due to default, as well as the right to monitor the level of wages paid to executives of rescued firms.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news yesterday a few minutes after midnight, after the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We've made great progress and we've come to an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Henry Paulson, an official in the Bush administration.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis that is happening on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the crucial point: if we don't do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be enormous," said Rep. Judd Gregg, R-Fla.
Over the past few hours, negotiations have been in full swing for fear of the effect that another failure would have on investors' moods.
The specified time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US presidency were invited to the negotiations later, and both expressed themselves in favour of an agreement, without neglecting to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has added some measures to the agreement, most notably one aimed at allowing owners to retain their homes and a measure on the wages of executives of state-rescued labor firms.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate ourselves on.
But these measures are necessary," he explained on the airwaves of television.
His Republican rival, John McCain, who was asked by another network if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough outlines I've read [show] that this is something we're all going to have to digest and with which we can move forward.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to buy up dubious debts and risky and unsellable assets of US financial institutions with taxpayers' money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis triggered by the bursting of the housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages, then spilled over to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in a cash freeze and the dismantling of banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of last week's first draft deal is due to Republican lawmakers.
Ever since the Democrats accepted that the government would only guarantee some of the "toxic" assets of troubled companies but not buy them back, the belief has been that the impasse is over.
In an effort to reconcile conflicting views in Congress, a provision was added stipulating that the government would be able to introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if it had to take losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan envisages a first injection of $250 billion, to which another $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
A further $350 billion is expected to be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for its help, Washington will acquire stakes in rescued companies that will pay it dividends if they make a profit, and which it can sell again when it is all over.
The federal government will have the option of delaying foreclosure procedures related to loans covered by the plan, as well as setting limits on the amount of remuneration and compensation paid to executives of affected companies.
The plan's architects would like to put it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against the project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's very clear that Washington doesn't hear you," said Rep. Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But making money off taxpayers is not the solution."
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the "Committee of Skeptics," presents the matter differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred esteemed economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and to carefully examine which path to take," he said yesterday.
At the same time, Europe has once again confirmed that this crisis is a world crisis.
At the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (USD 16.3 billion).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after French bank BNP Paribas announced it was pulling out of its purchase of its competitor, which is on the verge of collapse since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) to the subprime loan crisis in the United States.
Employing 85,000 people, Fortis is one of the twenty largest European banks and one of the ten largest insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"In return, we get the right to vote in the bank and influence.
That is what savers and households can appreciate in these uncertain times."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seems to have begun nationalizing another bank hit by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than $41 billion ($75.5 billion) were loans for the purchase of real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy the branches and accounts of the British bank's clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalised by the British government since the start of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a socially engaged icon
His beauty with azure eyes has long represented his trump card, according to others weakness.
Did this American actor break free from narcissism with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity and unflagging talent that possessed him also distanced him from the power category that produces real stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at 83 on his ranch in Connecticut from lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less spectacular than Brando, whom he resembled and had long been his rival on the big screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often begets beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was Hungarian.
From these European roots was born one of the famous faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because it saw this whole country in love with self-made man, a fighter in the Pacific War, wounded in battle, who studied acting at Yale in the early 50s, then visited New York's Actor's Studio and celebrated triumph in theater, television and soon in film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a race car driver who finished second at the 1979 Le Mans 24 Hours and a sex symbol, despite having formed a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him also leaves the dark places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the fuss of his own show-business, which will forever remain somewhat mysterious.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman's departure this weekend has caused film lovers to dizzy, as his big roles compete against each other on the black screen of memories.
After him, more than half a century of constantly changing American seventh art parades.
The charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) is remembered again, a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Roof, a 1958 adaptation of Tennessee Williams.
From a less distant past (1990) we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, disturbed at an advanced age by a marriage that did not live up to all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, the abused, violent, unforgettable delinquent in Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role intended for James Dean, taken over after his death that made Newman known in 1956.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, Oscar winner for Best Picture in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiard player in Robert Rossen's amazing The Hustler (1961), he plays the same character in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him his only Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
This face wandering through the ages, that was him.
And him again.
In his professional career, different eras compete with each other.
Young people know him mainly thanks to the cult Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 on the Coen brothers' The Hudsucker Proxy.
He ended his career as the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Road to Perdition Sam Mendes in 2003.
Unlike a few film legends who left the craft relatively early, Newman remained in the business for a long time, though he condemned Hollywood for its glitz, pomp and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, "a living challenge of underplaying", judging that he pushed too hard in his performances.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom roles came on a platter, the profession was not always so tender.
But he played the first lovers less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, scoundrels, and desperadoes, whose decline and rebellion were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known sides of his shy sensibilities.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, presents a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
In 1984, he dedicated the 1984 film Harry and Son, a work full of shame and sadness, to his son Scott, whom he lost to an overdose.
In the flurry of honors Newman received yesterday, his great friend and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (who played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) sadly declared, "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, such are the main qualities of the deceased actor.
Aside from his legendary career, he is also leaving a great fighter for civil rights, ecology, independent film, opponent of the decline of Hollywood.
We used to see his likeness on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, which we might find quite tasteless, although it was initially a gag.
However, the profits from the sale went to his Foundation for Difficult Childhood.
Rather than being lulled by fame, Newman became involved in society until the last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters containing these sentences: "Always and to the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
I was honored to be here."
And it was an honor for us to follow the career of such a prescient and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, a model citizen.
What was produced in the invoice factory Zuschlag & Co.?
Soon, on 8 October, the trial will begin in the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his associates.
The politician and his associates are accused, among other crimes, including forgery of documents, of fraud committed over a long period of time and systematically by a criminal organisation, as a result of which extremely significant damage has been caused.
According to the prosecutor's office, they used the money obtained in public tenders for their own purposes and often documented the completion of tasks with fictitious invoices.
Money from the state and local authorities - a total of approximately 65 million forints - went partly into the coffers of Fiatal Baloldal, partly into the pockets of individuals.
The method, which was also reported by the investigating authority, was that the money obtained in public tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration, and the undertakings entered into were never honoured.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were fake.
The forms for these invoices came from the Józsefváros market, the round stamps were made in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of the companies to be used for the production of invoices were decided, among other things, on a circular tour along the northern shore of Lake Balaton, on which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
According to his testimony, the former should have sought out guesthouses and restaurants.
In them, he asked for bills for his consumption, according to the model of which invoices were then produced submitted within public tenders announced, inter alia, by the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs, or the Self-Government of the Capital City.
Invoices were mostly issued by István Lados and his partner András Őri, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
During his "study trip" Lados found a pub.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and his associates in 2003, that restaurant catered to a group of ninety from Biztos Pont.
However, according to the company's manager, so many people would not fit into this facility at once.
Similarly, an invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért, later Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért, was rife with errors in form and content.
The guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms, more than ten people could not sleep in it one evening, yet the invoice stated one hundred and thirty guests.
However, the fillers of the forms with a rich imagination exaggerated it even when they mentioned on the documents a company also engaged in hospitality - Pigal s. r. o., in whose accounts, according to the information provided to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the documents in the names of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá did not even appear.
The head of the company, Győző Farkas, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he immediately knew they were false documents.
"Our business name and tax number were in the wrong place on the stamp."
As he added, in addition to the formalities, the fact that, according to the invoice, they accommodated a hundred people, because they have only eleven rooms that do not have such a large capacity, did not agree.
In addition, the invoice also indicated meals, and their restaurant has not been operating for a long time.
Eager invoice makers were also not convinced that the Budapest travel agency of their choice was only organising foreign trips, and they foolishly stated the invoice with payment in cash, which was also not in line with the company's invoicing practice, as a travel mediation service within Hungary.
Moreover, as it emerged during the investigation, they also mentioned VAT in the document, even though the organisation of travel to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
On the four documents issued to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation by Hotel Révfülöp s.r.o., the amount of VAT was disagreed, inter alia. The company's activities are not subject to the 25% but to 15% VAT, and moreover, the hotel employees issued only printed invoices, but the invoice produced was handwritten.
In addition, the "issuers" spoiled the invoice, for example, by stating in the case of one company, as it turned out thanks to an investigation by the public prosecutor's office, as an activity performed by road transport of goods, which the company originally based on investment advice did not perform.
The fact that the invoices issued to the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért foundations and to XXI Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont are false has also come to light because of formal anomalies - an inconsistent invoice format and a false stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna k.s. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied that they had issued the invoices.
For example, the counterfeiters did not notice that HIB s.r.o. from Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001) when the Fiatal Városért group was eating there, which is why, according to our information, the liquidation commissioner of the company also denied that he had issued the paper.
They issued invoices consciously
The second group of invoicers consists of those who knew that they had to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Eséla Budapestért Foundation issued accounts worth around four million forints for the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták.
According to the indictment, the head of Collab s.r.o. was forced to issue a fictitious account by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Zuschlag and his associates were also assisted by Biogate s.r.o., currently in liquidation, which in 2003 supplied the Jobb Jövőért Foundation and the Atlasz and Vörösfenyő associations with invoices worth around five million forints, behind which there was no real economic activity.
Not even the movement of money, because the created invoices were later canceled, which, of course, the organizations forgot to mention in their documents.
Another group of invoicing firms includes those that had ties to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was an authorized representative of the Ukrainian managing director of Delta Trió s.r.o., a company engaged in trading in fuel and motor vehicles, based in Budapest, where the company is not to be found.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of IT equipment worth approximately 18 million forints.
According to the information established by the investigation, these invoices were bought by the Kiskunhalas company Cash Investment s.r.o., which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The managing director of this company was a man from Romania, to whom Iván Kubatov was also supposed to hand over documents concerning the company in 2002-2005.
As we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he had issued invoices on behalf of the company to Atlasz, Hoppá and the Együtt Foundation and the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation and had himself accepted their consideration.
At the request of Iván Kubatov, the Romanian bricklayers founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s. r. o. and Jos-Investment k. s.
In fact, none of the companies operated, according to the defendant, because they did not get jobs.
Nevertheless, the undertakings benefited him since, at the request of the co-accused lawyer Zsolt Szente, who had also prepared their founding documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció linked to Zuschlaga.
On behalf of Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov gave the organizations a total of 15 invoices worth 14.2 million forints.
The prosecutor's office concluded that Kubatov had earned 10 percent of the amounts stated on the invoices and VAT.
To issue fictitious invoices, this time for a tender for the Biztos Pont association, the man also used the company Szi-Beri k. t.
In January 2006, the associations Y-Generáció and Szövetség and Modern Magyarországért submitted proposals for a public tender for the Mihály Táncsics Foundation (TMA), a public benefit organisation of the Socialist Party.
They received 500,000 forints each, but did not spend the amounts on the targets specified in the proposals.
To avoid this, TMA submitted five fictitious invoices from Works Team s.r.o.
Those invoices were also found during a search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
During the trial, some of the defendants will probably describe the process of production of invoices, as they have already done at the prosecutor's office.
It may be more interesting if the main defendant, János Zuschlag, decides to reveal everything himself.
His testimony so far is not very detailed, and although he has promised several times that he will explain everything at length, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest - in exchange for paying a large part of the damage, fifty million forints, perhaps the socialists have made a deal with him and Zusi will take it upon himself.
In the meantime, he may have been offended, as his requests for relaxation of the conditions of his detention, namely to place him under house arrest, have so far gone unheeded.
While economic criminals, who have done much more damage that they have not yet paid, are free to walk around or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he does not have this option.
The psychology of trumping: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue goods.
The neurological and economic underpinnings of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been uncovered by researchers in the fields of neurology and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don't want to fall behind in a competition like eBay, so they'd rather pay too high a price.
The research used an experimental auction to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a live-action auction, where the active brain areas of the test subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants could win money, but when playing at an auction, the important element of which is to trump the other side, a unit located under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively when losing.
This brain region, among many other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to the researchers, the price increase can therefore be explained by an effort to avoid a violent reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, members of the research team from the ranks of economists conducted a financial cross-sectional survey.
Under different conditions, three groups bid against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the fair value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of another group were promised that if they came out victorious, they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but if they lost, their members also lost that money.
The difference between the two groups, then, was that one was emphasized to win and the other to lose.
However, the "against losing" group members were willing to go higher than in the control and "winning" groups, confirming the neurologists' hypothesis.
"These results cannot be deduced from any pre-existing economic theory.
Until now, they have explained the phenomena observable in auctions by the joy of victory and risk avoidance.
Only neurological imaging has helped us resolve the contradiction between the two theories so that we have now arrived at a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed as the leading cause of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are being treated. The reason for this is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, hepatitis and jaundice, but the causative agents of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Depending on the causative agent, hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretions, saliva).
In any case, travellers should protect themselves by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against the type C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of infected food, usually they are accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, urge to vomit.
After that, jaundice forms on the skin and whites of the eyes, the stool lightens and urine darkens. Treatment can last up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people die worldwide from a more serious type of disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected people is medically treated.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, the causative agent of the disease destroys liver cells insidiously, so the first symptoms appear in many cases after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, carrying out regular screening is very important.
In three groups, the disease occurs much more frequently than average: among people who had blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can be demonstrated by routine laboratory tests, a person should contact his general practitioner if he notices any symptoms of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body to prevent contagiousness and prevent cancer.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organised globally by organisations representing patients in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
Benelux governments to nationalise part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries will help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to run into trouble due to the spreading effect of the US mortgage market crisis, with partial nationalisation: three countries will support a financial and insurance institution, which also has a capital stake in Hungary, with €11.2 billion.
This was agreed at the highest level this weekend by the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch Governments, attended by the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
Fortis is the first in the euro area to be plunged into a major crisis in the context of the crisis of the international financial markets, which has been spreading in waves for more than a year, and the decisions taken on this matter could, from a certain point of view, be seen as precedents.
Under the decision, which was made on Sunday night, all three states will buy out nearly half (49 percent) of the bank's assets.
The bank will most certainly sell part of its equity holdings, especially - mainly insurance - activities purchased last year from the Dutch bank ABN Amro.
