Who believes in God, doesn't it hurt so much?
According to recent research, belief in God acts as an analgesic that may have eased the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how belief in a god affects the perception of pain in humans, the British newspaper Telegraph reported.
In a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic worshippers and an equal number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while they all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, the Catholic faithful were able to eliminate much of the pain.
Thanks to a technique that examined the human brain in detail, it turned out that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first in a series of investigations involving academics, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
Exactly the test was carried out by attaching a sparking instrument to the left hand of the test subject, which emitted electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to stare at two paintings: Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary from the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci's Lady with an Ermine, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a certain state of piety in the faithful, while they chose da Vinci's painting because it is not very different from the first and has a calming impression.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner and during this time received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive sessions, while separately viewing a religious or general image.
Catholics reported that they felt "safe" at the sight of the Virgin Mary, as if they were "taken care of" and "calmed down, filled with peace."
When they watched a religious painting, they said they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image for atheists, as long as you need to find the right photo.
"We would have to find an image that they would perceive very positively, from the position of a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the findings.
"Practicing faith should and in many cases will change our personality," Wright added.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on regulating the pain of the faithful if they showed them a Madonna by Leonardo or a painter of similar caliber.
Would looking at a quality Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
You are what you share of yourself
On its tenth birthday, Google can claim that people can find it in their pockets at least as well as in the sky overhead; They know where they have been on holiday, what professional examinations they go to and what interests them.
According to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's CEOs, that's still not enough.
But when it comes to skeptics drawing parallels with Orwellian dark vision, the very nature of Web 2.0 is not clear to them.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, which is necessary for Google's founders to stick to their original purpose, which was, "Let's organize all the information in the world!"
According to a Google official, even after ten years of world-class work, the company is only at the beginning of being able to work with all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions such as "what should I do tomorrow?" or "what kind of work would be useful for me?" - such seemingly simple questions that software will not be able to answer until it knows enough about users.
Not all Internet users are well aware that Internet searches accurately capture the search words, from which IP address they were searched for and to which pages the interested parties moved after the search.
Thanks to the Personalized Search service, launched two years ago, users can, for example, keep their surfing history, they can look back at what they searched for and what they clicked, which in the long run generates findings that are much more tailored to them - the same logic will be used to base the Recommendations service, through which the system will offer us products and services based on previously indicated and retained preferences.
What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I do? - ask users who are afraid at the sight of Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the extent of the potential power represented by the company is more frightening, the counter-reaction does not evoke in Internet users a sense of guilt, fear of punishment, a desire for freedom, or even a rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all search terms are not only intercepted, but in justified cases may also be issued to a third party, in such legal cases the personality rights of Internet users are not protected.
Perhaps the best-known recent example was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that allowed the identification of pedophiles from Orkut's community sites.
Internet users concerned about personality rights could breathe a sigh of relief in May when the company, hand in hand with the electronic rights organization EFF, successfully proved its truth in a dispute with the FBI: Google must not be compelled by any constitutional article to provide any information secretly requested to the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully won nearly fifty thousand web addresses and a thousand search terms, citing the strengthening of the Child Protection Act passed years ago, but failed to get individual user search lists, or complete lists of websites and keywords spanning a two-month period.)
Opinion about Google is thus quite contradictory: it is being whipped by those who are afraid of giving up their personal data because they feel that their intimate sphere and private life will be harmed by starting to use Google's services, and they are acting against it with the revolt that belongs to multinationals with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and its wild offshoot, gathering around it enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users appearing in many countries, see in it a new generation of big business, a "corporation that is now in the works," unlike its rival Microsoft, considered the conqueror of the world because of Windows, even though they both fight for the same goals.
This may be due to the fact that, unlike Microsoft, Google does not require an identification code from its users and does not ask them to pay for its applications; An open, free and constantly fresh source of information and package of programs comes across as much more accessible, youthful, "cool" than the practice of the official software giant.
However, it may also be due to the fact that geeks understand exactly the very problematic relationship between the Internet and personality rights, which has brought with it one of the most talked about keywords of recent years: web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about nothing more than collaboration, about deliberately leaving traces behind us and using the communication channels at our disposal, and although their scope is different for everyone, the essence remains the same: we show ourselves.
The average young person can maintain a profile on several community sites from Facebook to Xanga, which they can easily connect with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm app that records the music they listen to, all of which they can then connect to navigation systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, in addition to writing a blog where their latest photo galleries will automatically appear.  which he stores on Flickr or Picas.
At the same time, we can read about a lot of exemplary cases that emerge: a girlfriend in the morning, looking at a flood of photos of mutual friends, easily discovers who her deceiving boyfriend spent the evening with, or a company can fire its employee just because she describes her honest opinion about the top management on her blog: one thing is certain, the concept of private life has been completely rethought today.
Whoever lives an online life consists of what he shows of himself, so we could define the basic thesis behind the behavior of today's youth.
And those who want to conceal something or at least avoid the Google monopoly have the option (starting with Scroogle, which uses Google's search system, but deliberately leaves no traces).
For example, a significant number of people deliberately do not register on community pages so that they cannot be found. Google's online apps, from a text editor to a photo editor and news portal, can be replaced with alternative versions that aren't connected to giant server parks and that don't build the best possible profile out of us.
Public opinion is not very secretly waiting for Google to show its teeth.
With its current value of $156 billion, the company is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising space is at risk for ad agency investment, and services introduced at an ever-accelerating pace are seriously making life difficult not only for Microsoft but also for many other software designers.
But critical observers also find counterpoints that are disturbing: for example, top management completely rejected employee protests after doubling the fee for a company nursery, arbitrarily frequent daily meals for employees were too expensive, according to management, but all this is lost in addition to the fact that Google bowed to the Chinese government in 2006 and filters out every finding under their agreement.  which is contrary to the good taste, or rather the interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal rules is that it never advertises new services in advance until they can be used, but what is certain is that the expected problems of the coming months and years could shake the world in new places: while some believe that Google's project to scan and archive books and magazines is becoming so large that the company will soon have to deal with the US Supreme Court.  others are terrified of her Health system, where we can build a complete health profile of our own with previous findings, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google is compiling a genetic database can serve as a good starting point for generations of science fiction writers, Cory Doctorow's famous novel "Scroogled" describes with Orwellian reminiscences a future in which humans can be intimidatingly well approached only with data from Google.
