Intelligent car imitates the flight of a bumblebee
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of avoiding collisions, if not imitating obstacle detectors found in the natural world?
For example, in bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprise project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC trade fair, was suggested to Nissan engineers by bumblebees. It was about building a new generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed the BR23C, a robotic minicar equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective cover," explained Kazuhiro Doi, the brand's general manager for technology PR and R&D.
An important role is played by compound eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions in a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eye, engineers reached for the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters in front of the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an operation to avoid a collision.
The obstacle is caught within a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to imitate the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid a collision.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
"If this were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the security containment, within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take no longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when dodging, the robotic car has only been able to rotate, accelerate and decelerate.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, what is important is instinctive, intelligent response, not the ability to process, much less store data.
This mechanism has to process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need for it to store and react using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few kilobytes of memory at all times.
It doesn't need gigabyte or megabyte memory.
It's the first step towards developing instant avoidance technology that Nissan estimates could make its way into production cars within a decade.
Another possibility of application can be the connection of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles lying in the way, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
Damn expensive child already has a name
The $700 billion economic rescue package bill, which is to be divided into several installments and aims to buy back low-quality bank loans, has already been written.
In the first round, half of the amount will be used.
After further negotiations that ended just after midnight US Eastern Time on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement in several days of debate on a $700 billion bailout package, Reuters reported.
"We've made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic speaker of the House of Representatives, who said all that remained was to write a deal.
The compromise on the package was also supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Commenting on the outcome of the compromise, Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said: "The programme will work and be effective, but more needs to be done."
The written form of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. Washington time (i.e. Monday at two o'clock in the morning Central European Time), but it did not cause any particular rise in the stock exchanges.
The 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, which establishes the program, will be voted on Monday first by the House of Representatives, then by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday night, after which news of the deal was welcomed at the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night and greatly appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
Indeed, the program differs from the Bush administration's original proposal, which called for the entire $700 billion to be spent at once to buy low-quality mortgage-backed securities.
It is now possible to spend a maximum of half of $700 billion in the first round, with $250 billion being used immediately after Congress is expected to make a decision on Monday and the Treasury to buy mortgage-backed securities that are judged to be of poor quality, the fate of the remaining $100 billion depending on the president's decision.
The program will be controlled by a special body, whose member will also be the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank.
The spending of the second half of $700 billion will depend on further decision by Congress.
The Ministry of Finance can use a combined tactic within the meaning of the law: it can simultaneously buy low-quality loans, mortgages and securities secured by mortgages, or other "poisonous" loans.
The buyout can take place in auctions or directly, ministry officials said.
The law will allow the firms concerned to participate in an insurance scheme in which the Ministry of Finance provides them with a guarantee for funds constituting cause for concern, in return for which the companies will pay a price commensurate with the amount of expected damages.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent demands of the US financial system, whether it is to buy the wrong funds on a large scale, to insure them, or to prevent the systemic risk associated with the collapse of a large financial institution.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the other hand, the heads of banks that are in trouble and are waiting for help from the state can count on the government to reduce their severance pay - which in overseas slang is simply called a "golden parachute".
Their disbursements will be limited only in certain cases, and these restrictions will depend on the method of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction essentially means that if the ministry buys at auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on the golden parachutes unless the fallen bank directors are sent straight into retirement.
In the case of direct purchases of low-quality loans, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the money for management is not excessive.
It should be added that the already existing contracts on golden parachutes will not change, the restriction applies only to new contracts, which should be an additional incentive to participate in the program.
"This is the first time in U.S. history that there will be a legal restriction on CEO compensation," said Barney Frank, Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the House Financial Services Committee.
In addition, the State will have the right to acquire a stake in the banks participating in the programme, thereby reducing the risk for taxpayers, since once the economy, and with it the rescued bank, is on its feet, they can also profit from the transaction.
The bill includes that over the next five years, the president must submit a proposal to Congress setting out how taxpayers can recover expected losses from the financial sector.
Of course, there were also voices on both sides expressing doubts about the plan.
"That's not what the American people asked us to do, because that's not going to protect taxpayers' dollars," said Republican Congressman from California Darrell Issa.
His Ohio Democratic colleague, Mary Kaptur, believes that the very people responsible for the collapse of Wall Street urged the provisions to pass.
Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office reported.
Export sales prices in industry were higher by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, down 3.9 percent year-on-year.
Producer prices in industry were higher by 0.7 percent compared to the previous month as a cause of changes in domestic and export prices, rising by 3.2 percent year-on-year.
Domestic sales prices in industry rose only minimally compared to the previous month, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in manufacturing sectors also increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest price increases in August 2008 were recorded in the leather and footwear sector (2.8 percent), mainly due to a month-on-month increase in prices in the leather and saddlery sector and 2.6 percent respectively.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly price increase in the chemical materials and products sector (1.6 percent).
Price reductions occurred in the oil processing sector (1.4 percent), electrical machinery and appliances (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimal extent - in the woodworking sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in the papermaking sector and publishing and printing activities remained unchanged.
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we measured price increases in the range of 0.2 to 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sectors, which have a strong weight in domestic industrial sales, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the continuing impact of the officially determined increase in gas prices from 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison of domestic sales in individual branches of the manufacturing industry, prices increased the most in the professional oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
A 13.2% increase in prices could be observed in the metalworking sector, while an 11% increase in prices could be observed in the production of food, beverages and tobacco products, which has a decisive weight.
Price reductions occurred in the textiles and textile products (2.5 percent) and electrical machinery and apparatus (0.3 percent) sectors.
In other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price growth ranged between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing sector rose by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sectors exceeded prices from the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In terms of industry focus, domestic sales in August showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) in the tangible asset production industries.
In the consumer goods industries, prices rose by 0.3 percent, while in the energy processing and processing industries, prices were unchanged from the previous month.
The largest price increase compared to the same month of the previous year in August 2008 could be observed in the energy industries (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods sectors, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent, while for tangible assets, we measured a decrease in prices of 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, falling by 3.9 percent in a twelve-month comparison.
In one month, our domestic currency depreciated by 1.7 percent against the euro, by 7.1 percent against the dollar, by 7.5 percent relative to the euro compared to August 2007 and by 15.9 percent against the dollar.
