Fox in the chicken coop
Life and health insurance companies in America often dismiss the possibility of taking out an insurance contract with a bidder based on people's drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that links the use of prescription data in each case to the consent of the person concerned.
It has to be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we're entrusting the chicken coop to a fox," said Richard Dick, author of a program designed to track prescriptions.
Insurance companies make premiums and amounts paid in the event of claims dependent on the health of the candidates, and if the risk is assessed as too great, they will not even take out insurance with it.
Previously, they sent people for medical examinations and concluded contracts only when they knew the results.
Ten years ago, Dick devised a much cheaper procedure: based on an identification number, the customer can easily find out from pharmacies what drugs the person has bought in the last year and a half, from which the program itself deduces what disease he suffers from and what his state of health is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it refers to the fact that he has a virtually uncontrollably high level of blood fats, which immediately puts him in the higher risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of them also determine the risk coefficient at the same time, so the insurance company has almost no work left except paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that some drugs can be used for several purposes, some compounds are usable, for example, against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
From the point of view of commercial insurance companies, these represent a significant factor in increasing risk, whereas the former are not.
In order to request and process the data, special companies have been set up to ask the patient for permission before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies.
They are now being forced to do so by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their previous negligence.
Some companies have recently been processing the results of laboratory tests, which they combine with data on the drugs used, thanks to which they can provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, while controlling its use will become increasingly difficult.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
A bill that will give authorities the power to audit businesses specializing in providing data is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: he has therefore developed his programme in such a way that the transfer of data is subject to the explicit consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that it is difficult for the person concerned to refuse authorisation, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
So the hens are still somewhat dependent on the fox's goodwill.
