Elites in danger
This phenomenon became evident a few days ago, when the House of Representatives voted against the White House's $700 billion rescue plan: a significant portion of Americans were more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, milder, welcoming to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which is conservative, hostile to "those in Washington" and to the world of finance, strong especially in the states of the central and south.
A soul that arrogantly showed itself in the vote I spoke of at the beginning.
But this thing just quoted is only an example of the changes, the great changes that the current economic earthquake is already showing: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In both the US and Europe, this crisis seems to be acting as an accelerator of phenomena that have been in incubation for a long time, that are consolidating in the new climate and are finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the reactualization, the extraordinary revival of the market, the double category of State-Power in relation to a certain renationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions, which, of course, have strong ties abroad, but in which, above all, the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state, are included to the greatest extent.
Which has created a political problem for those who run it at the same time: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are, among others, voters.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically world, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationality seems to be largely out of the question, or that it has little to add: the obvious proof is provided by the European Union, which is divided, as always, between different interests and different state strategies, and which is unable to decide on one common political line.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the government of each individual state, rescue plans, market recovery, new rules and, above all, the distribution of funds: at the moment when we are in distress, only the states have the economic means, the amount of financial resources, to be able to try to put everything in order.
And they possess the necessary means and justifications to use them: two sources of immense value, under certain circumstances, which perhaps no market and no international organization will ever be able to possess to such an extent.
This new emphase, which the crisis places on the state-national element, is, moreover, entirely in line with the increasing importance that recent economic advances are trying to attach to a factor closely linked to it: territorial jurisdiction.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the kingdom of the network, an increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, we suddenly realized that our future would have to contend more and more with such intangible things as water, grain, oil.
All things, who would have said so, may be transported from one place on earth to another, but they are in any case connected, absolutely, to a limited space, a territory.
So, who becomes their ruler, certainly has many more cards up his sleeve than who is not, and who has the misfortune to live in a place without grain, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, which, however, foresees a turning point.
