Super glue for walking on walls
Overcome the laws of gravity thanks to super glue and in the future walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the object of various American research centers, and now a team of four institutes has come very close to it.
Scientists managed to keep a hundred-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall using a sticker of only 2.5 square centimeters.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team of researchers is an evolution of existing materials that use a special carbon structure called carbon dwarf tubes.
"The glue base can be thought of as a series of tubes laid like an arranged pile of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists were inspired by the gecko's legs, covered with microscopic hairs that allow the animal to provide perfect adhesion.
Tests carried out on various materials, such as glass, Teflon and glass paper, have shown that the new glue is ten times stronger than the reptiles' feet and at the same time "simply detaches from the wall," explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton University's School of Engineering.
WALK ON WALLS? "This material could be useful as a makeshift glue," adds Liming Dai.
Perhaps to walk on walls like Spiderman? Perhaps, but researchers think of far less fascinating uses as a combination of electrical devices, because dwarf carbon tubes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering .
No super heroes yet.
OTHER RESEARCH – The University of California, Berkeley, is also researching a new adhesive.
In an article in the journal of the American Chemical Society, Californian scientists presented glue formed from microfibers as hair that cleans itself of dust by moving it across the surface to still maintain perfect fitness.
Medications: never with juices
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
If you take these drinks, which are consumed primarily in summer because they are refreshing and full of vitamins, along with some life-saving drugs, their ingestion changes the intensification or decrease in effectiveness with serious health consequences.
To highlight the risks of juices, both ready-to-eat and fresh, combined with the ingestion of certain medications, David Bailey is raising a new alarm at the ongoing 263rd National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia: one glass of grapefruit, orange, and apple juice is enough to reduce the absorption of some life-saving drugs, nullify their benefits, and put patients' health at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been accused of being responsible for increasing to toxic levels the effects of certain anti-arithmic drugs, antibiotics, anxiolitics, antihistamine and neurological drugs.
DRUGS AT RISK – The Italian Medical Agency itself announced this in a newsletter two years ago, urging doctors and patients not to underestimate the dangers of this mixture and to be careful about what they drink when taking medications, such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to experts, orange and apple juice also contain substances that suppress drugs.
A long list of effects inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, Director of the Department of Pharmacology at the State University of Milan: "Such discoveries are usually immediately reported to various international and national pharmaceutical agencies, which eventually arrange and exchange drug information instructions.
So always read the illustrative tickets of the medicines you get, and if you come across something unclear, do not worry, but ask the doctor or pharmacist for clarification," the expert told Ansa.
Nobel for Economics to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize was awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his studies of commercial models and localization of economic activities.
Krugman is a 55-year-old New Kenyan who teaches at Priceton University and is a well-known editor of the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the most important critics of the Bush administration's foreign, economic and policy actions.
