The plane of Steve Fossett, the millionaire who disappeared a year ago, is found
The remains of Steve Fossett's plane, a millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying over the Nevada desert, were found.
The wreckage was discovered on a plateau at an altitude of three thousand meters, in the area of Mammoth Lakes in the Sierra Nevada, on the border between California and Nevada.
However, there were no human remains inside the aircraft.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dispelled doubts that remained: "The plane has been found, we have sent a team there, and now we are certain that this is exactly the one Steve Fossett was flying in the day he disappeared," he said at a news conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old millionaire has been presumed dead since February.
The U.S. Transportation Security Administration (NTSB) reported that hours after the wreckage was detected, an investigation team was dispatched to identify the plane: it was Bellanca 8kcab, missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada, for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal belongings were found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents with Fossett's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and one jacket.
The search for Fossett was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire earned his place in history thanks to a long collection of firsts.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he became the first man to complete a trip around the world in an air balloon: two weeks of flight alone.
Three years later, he flew around the world in an airplane and without landing.
Among his many records is also a flight at an altitude of 15,445 meters, over the Andes, albeit with a co-pilot.
