Students victims of expensive rents - up to 900 euros per room
The rental market for university students knows no crisis.
According to the latest research by Sunia, a tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has already reached such proportions that entire layers of students have lost the right to study because of the overall too high prices that their families would have to endure – explains the head of the Sunia studios office, Laura Mariani – in this city the high demand from students has distorted the market in such a way that it has stimulated a process of price increases that has spread to residents."
In most cases, rental offers contain several offences: loose contracts, unregistered, no limited leases, associated subleases.
For Sunji, an exceptional intervention is needed that could regulate prices through a tax overhaul.
If we look at the details of the research, we will see that in Milan, in the Brianza area, about 450 euros are needed for one bed, for a single room you pay from a minimum price of 650 (Bande Nere zone) through a medium value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera zone) to a maximum of 900 (in the Vittoria zone).
In Florence, one bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, one room about 700.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in zones close to the university, 250/280 euros are needed for a bed in a double room, from 370 to 500 in a single room.
In Rome in the central university zones (San Lorenzo, piazza Bologna) they want about 600 euros for a single room, 450 beds in a double.
Prices are slightly lower (€550 per single) in zones close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
We only save if we move to peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single room zones Prenestina, Centocelle and the like.
In Naples you need 300/450 euros for a bed, for a room from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the zones Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari they want 250/350 euros for a bed, at least 350 for a single room.
In smaller towns, prices are definitely lower, but they have a greater impact on citizens' economies.
In cities like Perugia, where rents for students from outside the European Union are the most common phenomenon, another anomaly is finally being noticed: an increase of roughly 25-30% of the fee they want from foreign students, compared to Italian ones.
Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema, the city cancels the historical halls
Cinematographic historical halls are closing in favor of Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is like a blind one, it's like a face without eyes."
The painting offered by director Giuseppe Tornator successfully documents what is happening in the great Italian urban centers, but also in rural towns.
The process of cinema restrictions, the birth of large multi-screens in the suburbs and the subsequent disappearance of mono-screens in the central zones of cities, is one of the events that seems inevitable and irreversible, but it also has all the hallmarks of a real cultural crime.
Often historical places full of memories disappear, "it's like losing a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a part of the journey and a lot of emotions", feels the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that won an Oscar and the Grand Jury Prize at Cannes twenty years ago, and which told the poetry of a village cinema and the sadness of a way of life that cinema has probably lost forever.
The values obtained by Anec, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 traditional tip cinemas have closed their doors, and the highest bill has been paid mainly by the halls in the most important cities: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Torín, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna ranks first with a loss of 82 cinema halls, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And proof that the advent of the multiplex is the first responsible for their disappearance are the three Italian regions that have registered the highest number of new cinema multiples: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 more in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian approach has developed irrationally," argues Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the existing ones will survive, because when one cinema in a city closes, not all its visitors are willing to move to a multiplex.
Then let us not even talk about the insufficient subsidy for the fund in favour of the operators: the previous state debt is roughly EUR 10 million.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is a shame that the government does not respect existing laws.
Between €16 million and €18 million a year would be needed to support the sector."
Interesting is the Bologna case, the first Italian city to worry about road closures and which decided to find a way out by signing a protoculum between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas both in the historic centers and in the suburbs.
Among the planned norms are tax relief steps in favour of operators and benefits for the audience in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter a zone with limited traffic and will have special prices to stop and in some parking lots.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by introducing other measures."
However, it is certain that in order to stand up against the great power of the multiplex, traditional halls must improve the quality of sound and picture, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a topic that has always been important: the closure of the Super Cinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to found the "New Paradiso Cinema", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I walk in front of the already closed Rialto or Quirinal in the street Nazionale, where I shared so much emotion that I did not have to look at the inscriptions blackened by dust, I turn to the other side».
