When energy is born from waves, the big ones come into play.
It is an endless deposit that covers more than 70% of the Earth's surface and is now being discovered by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides, tides are new sources of inexhaustible energy on which the eyes of behemoths like Chevron have been glued, which is now trying to lay hands on these resources.
The possibility of generating energy from sea movements has been studied for more than a century, and in the 70s, in connection with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell around 1980, the idea of using marine energy fell by the wayside. But now environmental organizations and a new increase in the price of oil have given a new impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London said in 2007 that approximately 15 percent of the world's electricity consumption could be met by the movement of the waves of the seas.
That amount would be twice the energy currently produced at nuclear centers.
In addition, there are currents and tides.
Giants attack.
the company that bet on marine energy was Enersis, which agreed in 2005 to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When this intention was announced, it looked like a huge revolutionary step.
After two years of betting on marine energy, there are more and more companies that are betting on marine energy rather than traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology," a spokesman for a company linked to the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal — and they're thinking about working with us."
The cooperation we are considering concerns obtaining permission from the US Energy Commission, which is required to start a marine energy project in Alaska.
This signal cannot be underestimated, especially when we consider that it is in Alaska that the US continues to produce oil, and recently President Bush came up with a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York's Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey's Ocean Power are following the trail of marine energy, and the sums invested so far, while not known in detail, show growing interest, according to observers.
Technologies that need to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology that is still in its infancy, because it is not known what impact the use of marine energy will have on the environment.
For now, the facilities in Portugal and some in Scotland are small in size and do not seem to cause major problems for the ecosystem.
However, for greater energy production, it is necessary to use technologies with a greater impact on the environment.
The methods are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of fears that are interconnected with each other.
The force of the waves that move the buoys up and down is changed by means of cylinders and cylinders to the hydraulic pressure inside these buoys.
The pressure spins the turbine, which supplies power to the generator.
Energy reaches shore via submarine cables.
For now, four facilities of this type are in the project phase, awaiting federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for military purposes.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, is already generating power for the mall and parking lot using six pdsea turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water during high tide causes the turbines to rotate, which feed the generator with this rotational motion.
Verdant said they have a long list of clients waiting for the necessary authorizations to harness the energy.
After the waves, after the tide and after the tides.
The tidal potential deserves particular interest at this point, they say at the Institute for Electricity Research.
Although it is a discontinuous factor, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
New York, Maine, and Alaska, along with other coastal states, have already invested $7 and a half million dollars in tidal energy in 2008 and predicted investments of up to $35 million in 2009.
